commit_message:
Fix syntax errors in JSON examples

Many documentation samples include JSON which is not syntactically
valid. This change does not verify that the JSON samples included in
project are correct or used, but merely corrects the obviously invalid
sections of code.

Change-Id: I8539be30d41207befda004017664099471f28ab5

commit_message:
Sync some db changes from Oslo

Import two new db exception classes, and
sync many changes to openstack.common.db.sqlalchemy:
- models.py has better py3 support
- updated / deprecated option names in session.py
- many new functions available in utils.py

Change-Id: Ia7bac4ea61dbb8cb5baf6cf2064a94895cba3f2c

commit_message:
Enable access to admin openstack clients from benchmarks

Currently the clients() method of the base benchmark scenario class returns
python openstack clients for one of the temporary created users with non-
administrator permissions. This will be, however, insufficient for developing
benchmark scenarios for keystone, where access to admin permissions is
essential.

The patch adds the admin_clients() method to the base benchmark scenario class.
The method returns the requested python client with admin's permissions which
is initialized in the ScenarioRunner class.

Blueprint benchmark_scenarios

Change-Id: I1792d278bb972c0adcb8745f330f6d06b4bf0688

commit_message:
Administrator password injection

Describe how to configure Compute to support admin password injection.

Closes-bug: #1254563

Backport: havana grizzly

Backport notes:

- The dashboard configuration is landing in Icehouse, it's not in
grizzly <https://review.openstack.org/56151>.

- The Libvirt configuration option is called libvirt_inject_password
in grizzly. In havana, it's "inject_password" in the [libvirt] group.

Change-Id: I63e51ad7bf45387cb79d85e937a805b3804df41a

commit_message:
API: add a common base type

There are lots of common attributes so lets make a common
base type. We also want to make more common attributes like
project_id, user_id and timestamps.

Note:
- type and tags are now added consistantly on all classes.
- this requires a bit of correction in the samples

part of blueprint api
Change-Id: I777da24b8e1d0f9aed94650b645818814e631e0f

Don't use extra leading zeros in JavaScript

Fix code that causes JSHint to issue warnings about extra leading zeros
in number literals.

Change-Id: I51f30f069e8a4b3f6e3e4b00563abb23a399231f
Implements: blueprint js-coding-style-checks

www/.htaccess bad match

the source and target. should fix the subdir match error with the trailing slash
gets matched and doesnt get included on the redirect target.

commit_message:
Report transaction ID in failure exceptions

This way, when something fails in Jenkins, you have some chance of
searching the logs for the relevant transaction.

Change-Id: I3cf606cb4963e32b5c6ac3deda08e73541b3ff7d

subject: Handle IpAddressInUse with client exception

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-04 22:05:43.000000000', 'message': "Handle IpAddressInUse with client exception

Nova is not able to reliably distinguish between port OverQuota 409
errors and IpAddressInUse 409 errors when setting up networks for
instances. The client needs to provide a more granular exception so
nova can translate the error to it's own set of exceptions.

Also adds a test case for the exception_handler_v20 utility method which
was lacking explicit test coverage before this change.

Partial-Bug: #1247844

Change-Id: I71589097ae660c3385b3f4ff93ffae99ac7042b9
"}, {'created': '2013-11-25 22:00:35.000000000', 'message': "Handle IpAddressInUse with client exception

commit_message:
Handle IpAddressInUse with client exception

Nova is not able to reliably distinguish between port OverQuota 409
errors and IpAddressInUse 409 errors when setting up networks for
instances. The client needs to provide a more granular exception so
nova can translate the error to it's own set of exceptions.

Also adds a test case for the exception_handler_v20 utility method which
was lacking explicit test coverage before this change.

Partial-Bug: #1247844

Change-Id: I71589097ae660c3385b3f4ff93ffae99ac7042b9

There is no explanation of why we can't use a scope limited keystone token - generated by the conductor and passed to the kernel - for this. We should be using such a token rather than reinventing auth ourselves."}, {'account_id': 7711, 'date': '2013-11-25 14:07:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

lifeless, AFAIK keystone use two types of tokens: UUID tokens (deprecated, can be enabled by global keystone config option) and PKI tokens. PKI tokens (~5K) cannot be passed to deploy ramdisk via kernel command line (~2K hardcoded).'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-11-25 20:09:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

We discussed in the meeting - this is really a no-go.

Instead, put the PKI token in a file in the tftp root and read that from the ramdisk (you can see in the kexec element how to do that). And we then invalidate the PKI token after deploy.'}, {'account_id': 7711, 'date': '2013-11-28 16:53:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Allow vendor passthru without Keystone authorization

Vendor passthru API should be used for callback from deploy ramdisk,
but we must have a valid PKI token for authorization. This token
cannot be passed via kernel command line. Generalized deploy_key
used in this patch for validation for vendor_passthru.
PXE driver updated respectively.

Implements: blueprint vendor-lightweight-auth
Change-Id: I1df30c46785a81e70f3dec74a6f79887a7c8e217

commit_message:
Changes FakeMemcache to set token to expire on utcnow + 5 mins

fixes bug 1240994

keystoneclient 0.4 will use utcnow to compare expiration date.
The FakMemcache class sets expiration to datetime.now which sets
date for local timezone. If this timezone happens to be behind
utc the test will fail with expiration error because we are
comparing utc + 5 mins with utc - 1 or more hours.

Change-Id: I551506a5aaf0aef77476b11786399a66225603bf
(cherry picked from commit ac2a503d4d9ada69b5d5c1fbd2acf7397d8b4ac9)

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-23 07:40:25.000000000', 'message': 'instance will be stuck in unshelving state when unshelve fails

When unshelve an instance, if this instance has been offloaded,
the conductor manager will involve re-schedule for the instance.
If re-schedule failed to find a target host for the unsleved
instance, then the instance will be stuck in unshelving state.

This patch fix the issue as this: If re-schedule failed to find a
target host for unshelve the instance, then conductor manager will
try to rollback the instance to unshelve state.

Change-Id: If49b2d2c9263b853c745ce25fe146ade51948123
Closes-Bug: #1248799
'}, {'created': '2013-11-23 13:40:56.000000000', 'message': 'instance will be stuck in unshelving state when unshelve fails

When unshelve an instance, if this instance has been offloaded,
the conductor manager will involve re-schedule for the instance.
If re-schedule failed to find a target host for the unsleved
instance, then the instance will be stuck in unshelving state.

This patch fix the issue as this: If re-schedule failed to find a
target host for unshelve the instance, then conductor manager will
try to rollback the instance to unshelve state.

commit_message:
instance state will be stuck in unshelving when unshelve fails

When unshelve an instance, if this instance has been offloaded,
the conductor manager will involve re-schedule for the instance.
If re-schedule failed to find a target host for the unsleved
instance, then the instance will be stuck in unshelving state.

This patch fix the issue as this: If re-schedule failed to find a
target host for unshelve the instance, then conductor manager will
try to rollback the instance to unshelve state.

Change-Id: If49b2d2c9263b853c745ce25fe146ade51948123
Closes-Bug: #1248799

commit_message:
Unify different names between Python2/3 with six.moves

Some modules use different names in Python2 and Python3. Use six.moves
to make them work well in Python2 and Python3.
This is changes mapping:

six.moves      Python 2                 Python 3
builtins        __builtin__ 	        builtins
filter 	       itertools.ifilter() 	filter()
reduce 	       reduce() 	        functools.reduce()
reload_module  reload() 	        imp.reload()

Implements: blueprint make-python3-compatible
Change-Id: I97971f2ab40385bfc2c73ae7e8a7620c4d64a03c

Fixed Murano Platform tests

Added skip actions for all platform tests when
Open Stack does not meet to the Murano requirements.
This fix allows to resolve all false-negative tests results.

commit_message:
Improved logging in nailgun to simplify debugging process

We have several log files for nailgun app.log and api.log.
Also we have several threads. It was very difficult to find
out which part of log was written by rpc thread and
which by keep alive or web.py thread. Now we can use
standard bash utils to merge two log files and find specific
thread.

* move logs configuration in one place.
  Use single format of time and log format
  for api log and nailgun log.
* add thread logging
* add logging of milliseconds

Implements: blueprint nailgun-improve-logging-for-multithreading-app
Change-Id: I1d8816ad01c39de9602acdba8e99859d0fcd7a57

commit_message:
Make object compat work with more positional args

Currently object_compat would break if there is more than one positional
argument after instance, since the instance will be passed as a keyword
argument and there will be a positional argument passed as instance,
once we get to the actual function call - a TypeError will be thrown
similar to:

    TypeError: ... got multiple values for keyword argument 'instance'

This patch makes sure that the instance (if not found in kwargs) is put
back in the args tuple.

Change-Id: I5e9085e9f1bc1502f627eb9b206376cf39d58f39

The proposed solution is a good workaround for a seeming deficiency in the update_dict method, but is there a reason not to fix update_dict to properly handle values that evaluate to boolean false?"}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2013-11-16 10:36:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

That's the money question. The reason I did not do that is that I'm afraid I don't have the ability to know what will be the effect of such a change at this time. Any False values will now be explicitly sent, and as I'm unfamiliar with the coverage and functionality of our tests I think that it's unwise to send a patch that has the potential to introduce regressions that will not be caught by our testing suite.

On the other hand, theoretically, any regression introduced by such a change is a bug in its own right and should be caught and handled ASAP.

Any thoughts, or hunches as to what such a change might do?"}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2013-11-17 06:08:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I think the best approach is to always fix inconsistencies in the code unless you have direct evidence that the cost will outweigh the benefit.  If the tests don't exhibit problems, assume that there are none and rely on your reviewers to fact-check your assumption.  The alternative is that developers are afraid to change the codebase and things will never get better.

So, please submit a fix for the underlying problem."}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2013-11-17 14:38:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2013-11-17 14:46:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-11-17 14:46:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Before approval, I would like to see the commit message revised to indicate the 'why' of the change rather than the details of how the solution was arrived at.  Just as a patch submitted for review might hide the details of interim patches, so the commit message can exclude the thought process behind the interim patches."}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2013-11-18 09:14:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I think that the 'why' is covered in the 2nd paragraph?

The next two explain the implementation changes - I think it would be beneficial to keep that explanation, because I've often caught myself looking at patches from 1-2 years ago to understand the rationale of whatever inane code I happen to be looking at.

commit_message:
[fwaas] Can now create disabled firewall rules

Previously, the --disabled flag was ignored when creating
firewall rules. This patch fixes that problem, closes the bug
and adds a test. I changed update_dict so that values are sent
on to the API call if they are not None (So False values are
sent as well).

Before this patch, when creating a resource, values were
inserted into the API call only if their value was not None
or False. This worked fine for values whose default value
was False. 'enabled', however, has a default value of True.
That means that sending enable=False wouldn't work.

After the change to update_dict the issue, however, was that
'shared' and 'audited' were then always sent (Even if their
default was False) but the unit tests weren't expecting a False
value since it wasn't explicitly stated. Instead of changing
the unit tests, the solution is to only send the value in the
first place if it is not the default value, using argparse's
default mechanism. If it is the default, then it is written as
None and so is not sent, and not checked by the unit tests either.

Closes-Bug: 1250028
Change-Id: I142089ffd612fb52a326e8951a385920af852a2c

New patchset patch-id matches previous patchset, but commit message has changed.'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2013-11-13 15:28:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: (3 inline comments)

This is related to bug 1052535.  You might say it partially addresses that bug.  However, the real root cause for 1052535 is the bug in older iproute packages that entirely prevents the deletion of namespaces as long as any process is running inside a namespace.

The benefit of deleting namespaces is to prevent them from accumulating without bound.  We have observed some performance problems -- especially on older kernels such as Ubuntu 12.04's kernel -- where the neutron network host gets sluggish and unresponsive as the number of namespaces increases."}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2013-11-13 15:45:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

Back on the topic of auto-detecting capability in iproute.

I fear "ip -V" would not always be reliable.  As an example, our version is older but I've patched it to allow for namespace deletion.  I think adding detection for our special patched version of iproute would be a bad code addition.

I could write a script to detect the problem and run the script.  However, if the script fails, it would leave behind another namespace that could not be cleaned up. 

Although this is a good discussion, I would like for this patch to be accepted independently of this topic.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-19 23:36:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Optionally delete namespaces when they are no longer needed

Adds a configuration option to tell the network agents to delete
namespaces when they are no longer in use.  The option defaults to
False so that the agent will not attempt to delete namespaces in
environments where this is not safe.

This has been working well in deployments where iproute2 has been
patched with commit 58a3e8270fe72f8ed92687d3a3132c2a708582dd or it is
new enough to include it without being patched.

Change-Id: Ice5242c6f0446d16aaaa7ee353d674310297ef72
Closes-Bug: #1250596
Related-Bug: #1052535

[{'created': '2013-11-26 07:00:37.000000000', 'message': 'Fix some i18n issue in nova/compute/manager.py

Some exceptions in nova compute manager did not follow i18n coding

commit_message:
Add missing "interface" argument to AltManager

AltManager should have an interface keyword argument in the
initializer and also pass it to the super class.

Change-Id: I0d66609a7649d339f09b5948da5178df15ea43b2
Closes-Bug: #1255559

commit_message:
Add test_cases for cinder cli in v2 version

Add a new test_class for cinder-cli tempest in v2 version.

 + test_cinder_volumes_list_in_v2
 + test_cinder_absolute_limit_list_in_v2
 + test_cinder_backup_list_in_v2
 + test_cinder_extra_specs_list_in_v2
 + test_cinder_quota_class_show_in_v2
 + test_cinder_quota_defaults_in_v2
 + test_cinder_quota_show_in_v2
 + test_cinder_rate_limits_in_v2
 + test_cinder_snapshot_list_in_v2
 + test_cinder_type_list_in_v2
 + test_cinder_availability_zone_list_in_v2
 + test_cinder_service_list_in_v2
 + test_cinder_transfer_list_in_v2
 + test_cinder_bash_completion_in_v2

Three command-representations are different between v1 and v2:

 = cinder list
 = cinder snapshot-list
 = cinder bash-completion

Change-Id: Ia57af3cf3d8a0e62063ade1542c086e26f041e1e

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-22 22:57:39.000000000', 'message': "Ensure that resources are cleaned up when tests are skipped

Without calling tearDownClass explicitly, resources allocated
in the base classes are not disposed. This has a negative
effect on those resources (like routers, ip allocations
and such) whose quota's default values are low.

This fix may help address some of the gate failures seen
especially in relation to Neutron. It also explains why
during the neutron-isolated tests 79 routers are created
and only 75 are deleted.

Close-bug: 1253966
Related-bug: 1232971

Change-Id: Id86841775a26f12a5ae8c520a086e5f1ebd63135
"}, {'created': '2013-11-22 23:00:22.000000000', 'message': "Ensure that resources are cleaned up when tests are skipped

Without calling tearDownClass explicitly, resources allocated
in the base classes are not disposed. This has a negative
effect on those resources (like routers, ip allocations
and such) whose quota's default values are low.

This fix may help address some of the gate failures seen
especially in relation to Neutron. It also explains why
during the neutron-isolated tests 79 routers are created
and only 75 are deleted.

Close-bug: 1254166
Related-bug: 1232971

Change-Id: Id86841775a26f12a5ae8c520a086e5f1ebd63135
"}, {'created': '2013-11-23 00:54:05.000000000', 'message': "Ensure no dangling resources are left if tests are skipped

When tenant isolation is enabled, some network resources are
provisioned even though some tests are skipped. This has
a bad effect because these resources (like ip allocations,
routers and such) are created at an admin level and their
quota's default values are low.

Moving the base class setup after checking whether or not
tests can be run ensure no resources are left over. This
might help address some of the gate failures, seen especially
in relation to Neutron and tenant isolation. It also explains
why during the neutron-isolated tests the number of routers
created do not match the number of routers destroyed, even
when the run is successful.

Closes-bug:  1254166
Related-bug: 1232971
Related-bug: 1253966

Change-Id: Id86841775a26f12a5ae8c520a086e5f1ebd63135
"}, {'created': '2013-11-26 16:18:29.000000000', 'message': "Ensure no dangling resources are left if tests are skipped

When tenant isolation is enabled, some network resources are
provisioned even though some tests are skipped. This has
a bad effect because these resources (like ip allocations,
routers and such) are created at an admin level and their
quota's default values are low.

Moving the base class setup after checking whether or not
tests can be run ensure no resources are left over. This
might help address some of the gate failures, seen especially
in relation to Neutron and tenant isolation. It also explains
why during the neutron-isolated tests the number of routers
created do not match the number of routers destroyed, even
when the run is successful.

Closes-bug:  1254166
Related-bug: 1232971
Related-bug: 1253966

Change-Id: Id86841775a26f12a5ae8c520a086e5f1ebd63135
"}, {'created': '2013-11-27 02:08:12.000000000', 'message': "Ensure no dangling resources are left if tests are skipped

When tenant isolation is enabled, some network resources are
provisioned even though some tests are skipped. This has
a bad effect because these resources (like ip allocations,
routers and such) may have quota's default values that are
low.

With this change we ensure resources are torn down correctly.

Closes-bug:  1254166
Related-bug: 1232971
Related-bug: 1253966

Change-Id: Id86841775a26f12a5ae8c520a086e5f1ebd63135

commit_message:
Ensure no dangling resources are left if tests are skipped

When tenant isolation is enabled, some network resources are
provisioned even though some tests are skipped. This has
a bad effect because these resources (like ip allocations,
routers and such) may have quota's default values that are
low.

With this change we ensure resources are torn down correctly.

Closes-bug:  1254166
Related-bug: 1232971
Related-bug: 1253966

Change-Id: Id86841775a26f12a5ae8c520a086e5f1ebd63135

commit_message:
Adjust the order of notification for shelve instance

When shelve instance, if CONF.shelved_offload_time == 0, then the
notification order for shelve_instance() is as following:
1) compute.instance.shelve.start
2) compute.instance.shelve_offload.start
3) compute.instance.shelve_offload.end
4) compute.instance.shelve.end

This order is not correct, as actually before shelve_offload.start,
the instance was already reached shelve.end, so we should adjust the
order of notification for shelve instance as following:
1) compute.instance.shelve.start
2) compute.instance.shelve.end
3) compute.instance.shelve_offload.start
4) compute.instance.shelve_offload.end

Change-Id: I6e075b3f29e1c3f641ab1e459e1fbe3b05869a9a
Closes-Bug: #1248802

commit_message:
Fix for bug:1241379

Glance should not allow already uploaded images to be modified by
another upload. When configured with the local filesystem backend,
Glance prevents duplicate upload of an already uploaded image BUT it
changes the image status to "saving".

This fix ensures that the image (meta) data remains untouched. The tests
have also been augmented to check for whether or not the image (meta)
data has been changed.

Change-Id: Iac8c3011895d0f6b9793de4f5aca24a20b1ebc46
Fixes-bug: #1241379

commit_message:
Data processing: aggregation plots

This is the first contribution to the automated data processing and
visualization in Rally. Here we introduce the method for plotting
the relation between the values of some config parameter of a benchmark
scenario and its runing time. Minimal, maximal and average runtimes
are plotted, in assumption that the benchmark scenario has been run
several times during the task execution with different values of the
parameter the data is aggregated on (e.g. the "active_users" parameter).

The patch also extends the CLI with a new command, namely
"task plot aggregated <parameter_name> <task_uuid>"

Blueprint data-processing

Change-Id: Ieee6622f6cfdc737878a0217cf965307d739b2ce

commit_message:
Added LBaaS and FWaaS documentation for the NVP plugin

Added documentation to describe the LBaaS and FWaaS services when used
with the NVP plugin. The documentation points out the differences from
the community reference implementation and shows how to configure the
services with the NVP plugin.

Change-Id: I89a70b28d598e8405ebe6af0297a3d7be3255eeb
backport: none
Closes-Bug: #1247281

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-27 08:05:06.000000000', 'message': "Reduce unnecessary log chatter on context create

The context was previously logging at the 'warn' level when unknown
kwargs were being passed to it.  Since the agents were passing
tenant=None with each rpc request, this was generating an
unreasonable amount of log chatter that would not be useful to an
operator.  The fix is to log at the debug level instead and only
log parameters for which a non-None value is provided.

Change-Id: I5c328f628c597eb949c1fe67b23120d2b5d1c7da
Related-Bug: #1239923
"}, {'created': '2013-11-27 17:08:28.000000000', 'message': "Reduce unnecessary log chatter on context create

commit_message:
Stop logging unnecessary warning on context create

The context was previously logging at the 'warn' level when unknown
kwargs were being passed to its __init__().  Since the agents were
passing tenant=None with each rpc request, this was generating an
unreasonable amount of log chatter that would not be useful to an
operator.  The fix is to log at the debug level instead so that
the operators don't see the output by default but developers can
still choose to.

Change-Id: I5c328f628c597eb949c1fe67b23120d2b5d1c7da
Related-Bug: #1254530
Partial-Bug: #1255441

commit_message:
change create_test_server to create_vm

compute/base.py:create_test_server will run in all compute test classes if
use nosetests to run Tempest. Changing the name to 'create_vm' to fix the
problem for nosetests.

Change-Id: I81b374b9a43bb040c187019dbd1bcb3c4f56499c
Closes-Bug: #1255922

commit_message:
Add check_is_admin to common.policy.Enforcer

Currently we have no concept of admin-ness inside Heat, so it's
not possible for deployers to specify a hierarchy within a project
such that some users have more privileged access than others.

The first step is to provide a means to specify in the policy a
rule which describes who is admin, then we can correctly set
is_admin in the context based on that rule.

blueprint: request-scoping-policy

Change-Id: Idd1fb5f4e52bda87c70830d66e0c931bfe879347

[{'created': '2013-11-23 08:02:33.000000000', 'message': 'Improved debug ability for log message of cold migration

When cold migration failed because of nova scheduler return no
valid host, conductor only log no valid host, but did not specify
which instance failed.

This patch was specifying instance in the failure log for cold
migration.

Change-Id: Ia9e42f8f253323fb35a58e0be2a24ab043204d29
'}]
commit_message:
Improved debug ability for log message of cold migration

When cold migration failed because of nova scheduler return no
valid host, conductor only log no valid host, but did not specify
which instance failed.

This patch was specifying instance in the failure log for cold
migration.

Change-Id: Ia9e42f8f253323fb35a58e0be2a24ab043204d29

subject: Adds rpc method concurrency limiting support
messages:
[{'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-11-27 13:18:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Work In Progress

This is carried over from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56640/

There does not appear to be an equivalent home for the unit tests so have not carried them over yet.'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-11-27 13:41:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Do not merge

Thanks for the patch. From our IRC conversation:

 <markmc> "avoid specific concurrent operations from consuming too many system resources and starving other less resource intensive actions"
 <markmc> I'd like us to think about whether we can come up with a solution that fixes the problem for people, without them having to mess with this type of configuration
 <markmc> but yeah ... if we can't figure out a way of doing that, there is an argument for giving operators and interim workaround
 <markmc> dosaboy, I wouldn't be in favour of an interim fix without first exploring the options for a more fundamental fix
 <markmc> dosaboy, this isn't easily removable later, because once people start to rely on it we would need to put it through a deprecation period to remove it
 <markmc> dosaboy, also, an interim solution like this takes away the pressure on us to find a more fundamental solution ... and we may wind up never doing that
 <markmc> dosaboy, but, yeah - let's just discuss on the mailing list and see if anyone has useful input

commit_message:
Adds rpc method concurrency limiting support

This patch adds support to the amqp rpc driver for limiting
the number of concurrent operations for specific rpc methods.
This is intended to be an optional extension to the current
capability of limiting the rpc thread pool for all operations
by allowing an admin to limit concurrent operations based on
the type of operation being executed in order to mitigate
the load/impact that certain operations have on the node
they are executed on e.g. for lower resource nodes in a
heterogenous cluster. Operations that one might want to limit
could include migrations on a specific hypervisor or volume
formatting operations on a volume node.

Change-Id: I0fdc38f4b62be0efff863a52f432782a4ba366d2
Implements: blueprint rpc-concurrency-control

Edward Hope-Morley,

The idea of finer control looks good, but I have same concern with Eric Windisch. There is still something need be addressed.

1) what projects need this ?

I saw your blue print only above Nova, I think we need let this land in some projects firstly before into Oslo. See section "Principles" in https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Oslo

2)From your description about how to reduce workload. It seems doesn't make sense. We are controling rpc, Dose one compute node and 100 compute nodes need same value of these configuration options ? How can we know the exact value for different capability of compute with different cpu/memory?

I think we need more discussion :)'}, {'account_id': 6722, 'date': '2013-11-20 13:01:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Just remember another example. We have vmwareapi compute driver, one nova-compute process using one cluster in vCenter,
we can add new EXS host into the cluster, It's hard to figure out what the values of configuration options should be ."}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-11-20 13:20:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Changbo,

I'm more than happy to dicuss this. With regards to your points:

So for (1), currently our principle use case is for limiting specific actions in cinder, nova glance where we would want to reduce/restrict load on a set of nodes. The idea here is to avoid specific concurrent operations from consuming too many system resources and starving other less resource intensive actions.

As for (2), you would only set these parameters on the nodes that might be affected i.e. assuming a heterogenous cluster, some nodes will have fewer resources than others and that is where this aims to provide support. It is purely a devops extension for cases where they are concerned about certain operations/actions starving the node of resources.

As for your point about whether it should be implemented in a specific project first, since we require this in more than one project, I decided to put it directly into Oslo in order to avoid copy and pasting it to more than one project.

Do let me know if you have any other thoughts/concerns."}, {'account_id': 6722, 'date': '2013-11-20 13:33:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: No score

Edward Hope-Morley,

Thanks for your reply. You mean only set this on the node which is detected with heavy workload of OpenStack operations, right ?
I'm interested how we calculate the suitable values, these values depend on the capability of node. 

I just remove my '-1', let others review this :)"}, {'account_id': 159, 'date': '2013-11-20 14:01:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I still really would prefer this was implemented in the zeromq driver or, better, abstracted such that the same implementation works automatically in both drivers (either through more code reuse between the amqp drivers or doing this at a higher level).

The blueprint as written, in fact, is written such that it applies to RPC and not to AMQP. It isn't clear yet, but it is unknown if the upcoming Proton driver will be using the amqp.py, either.

Finally, which Doug and Mark can confirm, is that I understand that we'll no longer make these sorts of improvements or changes to oslo.rpc and new features should be moving into oslo.messaging instead. (This will also help with the cross-driver support)"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-11-20 23:06:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I think Eric is right, that this change should be made to oslo.messaging rather than the rpc code in the incubator. Mark, what is your opinion on that?"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-11-20 23:07:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Do not merge

In fact, I'll -2 this until we decide where it should live (which isn't a reflection on the quality of the code or the desire to have the feature)."}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-11-25 14:53:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Doug et al,

Could you please advise on how we can take this forwards? If oslo-incubator is not the pace for it then I am happy to move it to oslo.messaging or wherever is appropriate but I'm not clear on what the next step is here."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-11-25 17:43:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Edward - Mark McLoughlin leads the work on oslo.messaging, so the best thing to do is ask him directly. If you use email for that, please copy me.'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-11-26 12:08:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Do not merge

commit_message:
Adds rpc method concurrency limiting support

This patch adds support for limiting the number of concurrent
operations for a particular method. We already have the ability
to limit the size of the rpc thread pool but this extends that
ability by allowing an admin to limit threads based on the
operation they are executing. This would be useful for limiting
load on nodes that have reduced resources.

Change-Id: Ieef756afe88d335059fc75484dc129a3c6739b3c
Implements: blueprint rpc-concurrency-control

commit_message:
Improve a boot-seed-vm status message.

In boot-seed-vm we are dealing both with the image and the VM. We now
print a slightly more clear message about which one we are detecting is
not currently present.

Change-Id: Icd12e25d1cce8a19a17d366e864b2bf1379f4761

commit_message:
Use [] for new arrays in JavaScript

Fix the code that makes JSHint issue warnings about the use
of new Array() instead of [].

Change-Id: Id00e938d4c4df7da92397f4cf84da7d32ee5e7b8
Implements: blueprint js-coding-style-checks

commit_message:
Ensure all compute meters are listed in dropdown

Fixes bug 1243298

Previously, an incomplete list of Compute (Nova) meters appeared
in the Metric dropdown on the Stats tab of the admin/Resource Usage
panel. As a result, some meters were inaccessible via the dashboard.

Now, a complete list of the current set of Compute meters is constructed
by querying all meters known to the ceilometer API and cross-referencing
with the resource IDs known to refer to instances.

Change-Id: I456bb0282ad465f0cc346e2e076545fbf1bc1346
(cherry picked from commit 264a595cba4e6a7a01cecb64024b18d67971eac4)

commit_message:
Use model_query() instead of session.query in db.instance_destroy

Unify db.instance_destroy() method to use model_query() as others
methods use.

Side effect we won't try to soft delete already soft deleted instance

Change-Id: I36d5bb42b16901c260ff4276e31a6aec46ffa8a4

commit_message:
Catch error deleting trust on stack delete

When deleting a stack, it's possible for deleting the trust to fail,
for example if the user deleting the stack is not the user who created
it, or an admin (which raises a Forbidden error), or due to some
other transient error e.g connection to keystone interrupted.

Currently in this case, we fail to mark the stack deleted in the DB
and leave the status "DELETE, COMPLETE", which is misleading.

Change-Id: Ie8e9ea48bc4f44e56ff4764123fcca733f5bd458
Partial-Bug: #1247200

commit_message:
Add port address unique constraint for sqlite

SQLite backend used in unit tests, but unique constraint for 'address'
column in 'ports' table not working for this backend. Patch fix this
and also unit tests which violates 'address' UC.

Closes-Bug: #1252343
Change-Id: I761e480c99f1687531cf4c64a64c02faa7e4fb73

commit_message:
Switch on coverage support for unit tests

After we merge this patch we can use 'tox -e cover' and see how is our
code is covered with tests. It's very good for proper code process.

Change-Id: Ia39145727b0dc55879cd807e2ef4fc2de331c9a4
Implements: blueprint coverage-for-testr

commit_message:
Honor endpoint_type when requesting keystone for a token

The parameter 'endpoint_type' must be taken into account in case
one has different public and internal Heat endpoint

Change-Id: I63ffbec321e187f42405e1e70781065a274004d2

commit_message:
Run puppet in debug mode if 'debug' fact is set

Also add a --trace permanent option for puppet run.

BP fuel-enable-debug-in-cli https://blueprints.launchpad.net/fuel/+spec/fuel-enable-debug-in-cli

Change-Id: Ia8ab8878d755559377e4e87f38c5033dfa4715b4

commit_message:
Ensure that members is a list

self.properties.get('members') should not be None.  Ensure that
an empty list is returned instead.

Change-Id: I01d191eafebac30ad25505b312ff6e936181bdbf

commit_message:
Fix typo error in README.rst

From source code we can see the config file should be
/etc/os-collect-config.conf instead of
/etc/os-collect-config/sources.ini

Change-Id: Ieb1149991c4009fe05610ee5737d320274597404

[{'created': '2013-10-29 17:05:55.000000000', 'message': 'Style improvements to logging format strings

Added the following improvements:

* Use the logging API to handle formatting of message args, which
  potentially prevents us from having to do a bunch of redundant string
  formatting for logging statements which occur below the runtime's
  logging level. For example, in many places `LOG.debug('foo %s' % bar)`
  has been replaced with `LOG.debug('foo %s', bar)`.
* A few of these logging statements were missing the i18n `_(...)`
  around the message text.
* One these statements included some unnecessary escaping in the log
  message string (e.g., 'foo is a \'bar\'', which was replaced with
  "foo is a 'bar'").

Change-Id: I9080aebdf0ce0e719949d009e0ab85bfc6be8646
Closes-Bug: #1234283
'}, {'created': '2013-10-30 13:08:39.000000000', 'message': 'Style improvements to logging format strings

Added the following improvements:

* Use the logging API to handle formatting of message args, which
  potentially prevents us from having to do a bunch of redundant string
  formatting for logging statements which occur below the runtime's
  logging level. For example, in many places `LOG.debug('foo %s' % bar)`
  has been replaced with `LOG.debug('foo %s', bar)`.
* Similarly, this change also removes a few redundant repr() and str()
  calls. For example: `LOG.error('foo %r', repr(bar))` ->
  `LOG.error('foo %r', bar)`, and the same for %s/str().
* One logging statement included some unnecessary escaping in the log
  message string (e.g., 'foo is a \'bar\'', which was replaced with
  "foo is a 'bar'").
* Added some missing message translation calls.

Change-Id: I9080aebdf0ce0e719949d009e0ab85bfc6be8646
Closes-Bug: #1234283

commit_message:
Style improvements to logging format strings

Added the following improvements:

* Use the logging API to handle formatting of message args, which
  potentially prevents us from having to do a bunch of redundant string
  formatting for logging statements which occur below the runtime's
  logging level. For example, in many places `LOG.debug('foo %s' % bar)`
  has been replaced with `LOG.debug('foo %s', bar)`.
* Similarly, this change also removes a few redundant repr() and str()
  calls. For example: `LOG.error('foo %r', repr(bar))` ->
  `LOG.error('foo %r', bar)`, and the same for %s/str().
* One logging statement included some unnecessary escaping in the log
  message string (e.g., 'foo is a \'bar\'', which was replaced with
  "foo is a 'bar'").
* Added some missing message translation calls.

Change-Id: I9080aebdf0ce0e719949d009e0ab85bfc6be8646
Closes-Bug: #1234283

commit_message:
PasteConfigNotFound also raised when keystone.conf not found

Although keystone is looking for paste configuration on startup, this
exception can also be raised when keystone attempts to look in the
regular keystone.conf file for paste configuration, and can't find that
file either. The solution here is just to make the exception slightly
more generic (ConfigFileNotFound), along with it's rendered error
message and improve surrounding comments to better explain the scenario.

Change-Id: I88f1d987113884097b1cdf8c120613613abfb8c9
Closes-Bug: 1254036

commit_message:
Make Japanese doc link clicked

In addition, the following are changed:
- Rearrange navigation dropdown menu
- Change charset from ascii to utf-8 because index.html now contains
  UTF-8 characters.

commit_message:
Create_volume api works with TaskFlow 0.1.1

TaskFlow requirement was added to Cinder.

Cinder API.create, VolumeManager.create_volume
and SchedulerManager.cerate_volume commands
were reimplemented to work with TaskFlow 0.1.1

VolumeManager.create_volume was implemented as four separate
flows to create volume: from snaphot, from image, from source
volume and from nothing.

Implements: blueprint create-volume-flow
Change-Id: Iaf269dddf351122cf3fb611ceb632f8bd688f9a9

commit_message:
Deleting statistics tables from resource usage page

The tables were interpreting the stats in a wrong way, for some stats
it's not even easily possible to get those stats. We need to go through
each statistic separately and document it in the Ceilometer docs first.

Then it's more likely that these table stats will be distributed in
various tables in dashboard in the form of sparklines so these pages
won't be needed.

Fixes bug 1249279

Fwaas can't run in operating system without namespace feature

Adding the check before generating the local_ns_list
to fix the issue.

commit_message:
Make tokens work with --os-no-client-auth

Currently --os-no-client-auth assumes you'll only ever want to pass
a username and password to the standalone auth_password middleware,
but it's also valid to pass a token and endpoint, which can then
be used to either connect to a normal (non-standalone) Heat without
needing the client to connect to keystone, or pass a token to custom
auth middleware in standalone mode where tokens are accepted.

e.g:

heat --os-no-client-auth
      --heat-url http://127.0.0.1:8004/v1/<tenant ID>
      --os-auth-token <a token> stack-list

Change-Id: Ie22c85ba5b3b987505f4d6204b4dd6ff03e0d912
Closes-Bug: #1252248

commit_message:
Fix shell operation with --os-auth-token

Currently the --os-auth-token/env[OS_AUTH_TOKEN] case doesn't
work, as we always expect a username/password to create the
connection to keystone.  This enables the client to be used
with only a token and tenant (which is required for keystoneclient
to retrieve the catalog) specified, e.g:

heat --os-auth-url http://127.0.0.1:35357/v2.0/ \
     --os-auth-token <a keystone token> \
     --os-tenant-id <tenant ID> stack-list

Change-Id: I478ce178f44e42c68153f1b347c6144f0a133f5b
Partial-Bug: #1252248

Add volume migration code to Nexenta iSCSI volume driver

Utilize ZFS-specific optimizations for direct host-to-host
volume migration

DocImpact

commit_message:
Parse out '@' in volume['host'] to do discovery

The backup method of getting iscsi info is to use
iscsiadm discovery, however currently that method
just uses volume['host'] which in the case of
multi-backend will use "host@backend-name".

This will cause the discovery to fail of course, so
this change just parses out the '@' symbol if it's present
and avoids the problem in the first place.

This also beefs up the error logging and exception catching
a bit.

Parsing out the '@' symbol all the time should be safe as
the accepted valid chars for hostnames are digits, a-z and
hyphens.

Change-Id: Ic45a38bf4c56a4aec6847ab0d29e3b41d35bd3d2
Closes-Bug: #1250673

"}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2013-11-13 16:53:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I like this concept; it is in the same general direction I saw quotas going next.  There are a few caveats, though:

1. I believe there are cases where reservations are made in one function, but must be committed (or rolled back) in a completely different function.  There are also cases where we do a rollback if an error occurs, but not a commit.  I believe all of these can be accommodated with your QuotaReservation object, but it may require using methods on the object.

2. I would almost rather __enter__() raised an exception than returning None, but I haven't experimented with raising exceptions from __enter__() to see what would happen, so that may be what you have to do.

3. I wish we would raise just OverQuota all over Nova, but I think unfortunately that's more of an architectural limitation.

4. The reason for the -1 is the lack of tests.  Also, I would like to see thorough docstrings to match the ones I wrote in the quota system."}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2013-11-13 17:34:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Let me answer every point one by one

1) I agree that we should add some more functionality to reservation object (commit, rollback, etc.) so it can be used to control the process.
However I think that in future additional refactoring should be made to avoid cases when reservation is created in one function and committed in the other. From my point of view such approach leads to unnecessary code complexity and potential resource leak.

2,3) Yes raising exception would be the best option but it will require additional changes in exceptions handling all over Nova.

4) I will add docstrings and tests for enter/exit methods for the new class.'}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2013-11-13 17:47:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

1. Oh, agreed; but I'm not convinced that it can be done just yet.  If I remember correctly from when I wrote quotas, there were cases where I had to pass reservations to a completely different host.

2. This may still be possible; you would just need to wrap the "with" block in a "try" block.  Still, that may be undesirable…

3. Indeed; that's what I was pointing out with my comment on the architectural limitation (read: "exception explosion")

4. Thanks :)  But it should be for more than just __enter__() and __exit__(), of course.'}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2013-11-20 09:40:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Work In Progress'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-11-28 06:03:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Current quota implementation is quite complicated and error prone.

commit_message:
Refactoring of Quota system, Added guard objects functionality

Current quota implementation is quite complicated and error prone.
We should try to make quota usage more transparent to make it simpler
By using object guard we can simplify error handling in quota API.

This change is the first example of how guard objects can be used.
Later same approach can be used to refactor most of the quota usages

Change-Id: If3249bda75719b957ded015d68e9b2f6f2347723

'}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2013-11-13 04:36:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Angus, the problem I am trying to solve here is:

Users find it difficult to generate their own random looking passwords.

This patch solves the problem, because it allows the RandomString to be used in conjunction with a string parameter. 

Imagine a template with the following parameter:
  password:
    description: A password
    type: String
    required: false

The string "password" parameter would not be required, and by setting the property, override_string: {get_param: password}, on a RandomString resource, a password would be generated conditionally based on if the password parameter value was submitted.'}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2013-11-13 07:22:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Can't you do it the other way around though? Have the default of the password be the random string resource, and the value be the parameter?"}, {'account_id': 7135, 'date': '2013-11-13 07:51:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Would it be better to have an intrinsic function to return the first non-empty value in a list?'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2013-11-13 08:55:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Andrew: I agree with Angus. It's seems really odd. According current code changes user can set his own password in template. 
Firstly in this case RandomString resource will be have only one purpose - it's storing this password (no generation and randomization for key). For same aim you can use parameters section. 
Secondly, as far as I know random password needed for improving security. But if you set {override_string: password}, this 'password' will be avaliable from template for anybody.

Also you said about some problems for users when they generate own random passwords. I find it strange, because current resource resolve this problem fully. If user doesn't know what choose in properties, then he may use default values."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-11-19 17:31:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

This is indeed backwards from the way people would want to think about it.

If anything, we should enable parameters to have a randomized string as a default. AFAIK, that isn't possible today because parameter defaults are parse-time things.

This is another use case for "components" in templates which are fully available to the entire template at parse time and don't wait for the "create" step. The random string generator would work fine for that as it has no external dependency.

So I think this feature needs to be rethought at a larger scale, and if it is considered a bug, there are plenty of workarounds already.

Also, -1 for a change in behavior without a bug or blueprint.'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2013-11-20 11:56:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Add ability to override the RandomString value

Give the RandomString a parameter that allows an arbitrary value to be
resolved via the value attribute. This gives the RandomString resource
the ability to be used as a default for a string parameter.

Change-Id: I41d080a45c9f85303c2d91a879cd03b0b8c87d98

[{'created': '2013-10-03 01:49:56.000000000', 'message': 'Double test processes.

* tools/pretty_tox.sh: When running tests in parallel double the test
processes to better deal with IO. This is an experiment to see if tests
fail under the extra parallelism and to see if it helps test run time at

commit_message:
Double test processes

* tools/pretty_tox.sh: When running tests in parallel double the test
processes to better deal with IO. This is an experiment to see if tests
fail under the extra parallelism and to see if it helps test run time at
all.

Change-Id: I04bf3678e694419eab42614ff425fd166f58bb4c

commit_message:
Configure glance workers

The glance configuration sample recommends to configure the workers to
the number of CPUs.

This change improve the performance, however sever type of concurrency issue
 will have smaller chance to be triggered at gate time.

Change-Id: I395409036c55f10a90a56498251bf756c6989745

Create accrc file only to the demo user by default

Creating certificates is time consuming operation, and on gate time we
only use the demo user's accrc file.

Change-Id: I9c55d1c44c1bfde98b9d9751ed8bec53dbdb4825

commit_message:
Add debug logging options to unit tests

This allows to see logging in unit tests on debug level.
The user can choose it when running testr, from
choosing OS_LOG_DEBUG=1 testr run <test>. Default is 0.

This helps identifying if the right methods are being
called during unit tests within the stubbed ones.

Change-Id: If0b82faf11c6179ea8b15005e9a54324167af445

Is there already an identified use for these modules outside of keystone, or is that just a "could happen" case? I'm trying understand the reasoning behind bringing the code into Oslo first.'}, {'account_id': 8116, 'date': '2013-11-13 00:04:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (7 inline comments)

With respect to Doug's question asking why not add this to Keystone first. That was the original idea. Add it to Keystone first and then because these utilities have general use and applicability move them to Oslo to expand the base of common code.

Reviewers in Keystone NAK'ed the submission requesting instead these changes go directly into Oslo first, although there were other comments in this vein please refer to this:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/49452/4//COMMIT_MSG

That speaks strongly for their desire to import this into Oslo first.

Having worked extensively with x509, SSL/TLS, etc.in the past we have always found a need for manipulating PEM data, this is why I don't think the utility is limited to Keystone only. At a minimum python-keystoneclient will likely to need to interact with x509 data. As more support for SSL makes it into OpenStack the likelyhood of other projects needing to manipulate x509 data will grow. The division of the utility code into two logically distinct modules should furhter serve to make the code generally useful.

In general I would like to see OpenStack have a much richer set of common library code, the amount of current code duplication is problematical. Where possible we should be encouraging the coalescing of common code and discouraging duplication and reinvention."}, {'account_id': 8116, 'date': '2013-11-13 00:11:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-13 00:15:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Two Python utility modules for PEM formated data

These utilities were primarily written to address needs in keystone
but they are general purpose and can be use elsewhere in
OpenStack. The original idea was to add them to keystone and then move
them to Oslo. Inclusion in keystone was NAK'ed saying they needed to
land in Oslo first. They form the basis for fixing keystone bug

base64utils provides functions for manipulating base64 data.
pemutils utilizes functionality in base64utils.

base64utils provides functionalty to:

* tests if text is valid base64
* filter formatting from base64
* convert base64 between different alphabets
* Handle padding issues
    - test if base64 is padded
    - removes padding
    - restores padding
* wraps base64 text into formatted blocks
    - via iterator
    - return formatted string

pemutils provides functionality to:

* parse text and find all PEM blocks contained in the
  text. Information on the location of the block in the text, the
  type of PEM block, and it's base64 and binary data contents.
* Search text for only a specfic PEM type (e.g. certificate)
* parse text assumed to contain PEM data and return the binary
  data.
* test if a block of text is a PEM block
* convert base64 text into a formatted PEM block
* convert binary data into a formatted PEM block
* access to the valid PEM types and their headers, including
  conversion from deprecated PEM headers to the canonical header
* Format either base64 or bindary data into PEM format

Change-Id: I7c4d04e4b29a46379c33e662441a5139d80ecfaa
Partial-Bug: #1233838

commit_message:
VMware: bug fix for incomplete statistics/datastore reports

There are certain cases when the VC may return partial results. An
example for this is when it does not have access to the datastore,
for example there may be network problems. In a case like this we
enable a retry to get the resource data. There are two cases where
the full results are critical:
1. statistics retrieval - if invalid statistics are reported then
this may cause scheduling to fail
2. datastore retrieval - if a datastore is not found then VMs may
not be deployed or deleted

Change-Id: I2e451f6c0063ffac457dc5b3d8e2853b5df5a09f
Closes-bug: #1252827

commit_message:
Let resources decide when to update

Previously, the StackUpdate code decided when an update was necessary for a
resource. However, all of the information required to make this decision is
available to the resource, so push this decision into the resource so that
it can implement custom behaviour if necessary.

Change-Id: If098424cf2502c02bad4194d509393d198d8745f

commit_message:
Add logging configuration for iso8601 module

iso8601 module outputs log messages but it is not useful for users,
so this commit assigns null log handler to iso8601 module.
This change suppresses iso8601 log messages during unit tests.

Also moves openstack_dashboard related logging config for unit test
from horizon to openstack_dashboard.

Change-Id: I01cf12688118e2137382b8dc7a050b3587749354
Closes-Bug: #1250554
(cherry picked from commit 1f81be7e671a11449911f84f9f2d74c220dbc8cc)

[{'created': '2013-11-21 21:12:59.000000000', 'message': 'Handle IPAddressGenerationFailure during get_dhcp_port

If a network/subnet is deleted while the dhcp agent is trying
to get/create a dhcp port for that network, the exception
will be raised because no IP Allocation Range is available.

However, this particular failure mode causes just noise, because
the dhcp agent can cope with it without problems.

A follow-up patch will deal with the other exception traces during
create_dhcp_port

Partial-bug: #1253344

Change-Id: I7fe35455ce905daa22ff96367e120864a7d3fb92
'}]
commit_message:
Handle IPAddressGenerationFailure during get_dhcp_port

If a network/subnet is deleted while the dhcp agent is trying
to get/create a dhcp port for that network, the exception
will be raised because no IP Allocation Range is available.

However, this particular failure mode causes just noise, because
the dhcp agent can cope with it without problems.

A follow-up patch will deal with the other exception traces during
create_dhcp_port

Partial-bug: #1253344

Change-Id: I7fe35455ce905daa22ff96367e120864a7d3fb92

commit_message:
Handle NotFound exception in snapshots API code

Passing tests in the gate leave unhandled trace/error messages
for a VolumeNotFound issue.

These are caused by the test_volumes_snapshots_negative test
which requests a non-existent volume and the tests pass however
the log files are a bit messed up due to the unhandled exception.

This change just adds a try/catch block around the volume get calls
in the snapshot modules and raises HTTPNotFound as appropriate.

Change-Id: I2096f2da7c68ef7924fc8e69b2d5c2afea578512
Closes-Bug: #1255214

'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-09-30 18:49:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Armando,

Please take a look at the ML2-specific fix related to port and subnet auto-deletion in delete_network() in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48765/, and also at the discussion in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48546/, a previous approach to fixing the same issue in NeutronDBPluginV2.delete_network(). I see now that this also applies to auto-deletion of ports in delete_subnet(), so the ML2-specific fix needs more work. 

Do you think the approach taken in ML2 should be implemented in NeutronDBPluginV2 for all the auto-deletions, letting the plugins' normal delete_[port|subnet]() methods handle them (outside of the transaction)? This risks breaking plugins that currently attempt to deal with the base class's DB-level-only auto-deletion, but seems like the right approach.

-Bob"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-10-01 21:25:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Hi Bob, thanks for looking at the patch and for proving input to how ML2 handles these sorts of issues. My personal preference would be to have a clear cut between the responsibilities of the base plugin (db) and the derived plugin (core). I think that mixing parent and child logic should be avoided in order to prevent unexpected behaviors or side-effects from occurring, and as a consequence, making hard to produce fixes. So I would be against the idea of having the base plugin 'delegating' operations to the derived ones, but I recognized that's how it's being done in some places so far. So in a nutshell my preference would be that the code in NeutronDBPluginV2 should be all about handling DB operations and should avoid relying on the core plugin. On one extreme, I would even advocate for breaking the hierarchy and use composition instead; but with so many interactions involved even with a simple net-create operation...keeping things separate may be the right way to minimize interdependencies."}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-10-08 21:30:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

Auto-deleting subnets seems to also require with_lockmode('update')."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-10-08 21:35:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (1 inline comment)

Thanks Bob!'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-10-09 03:20:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2013-10-09 04:14:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

If cascade deletion of subnets and ports is required, why is it implemented half-hazardly in code rather than declaratively in the database?  Other attributes of the Subnet model have this relationship declared, and it's not clear to me why the most common relationships would not use cascade deletion."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2013-10-09 04:29:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

If the database uses cascade to automatically delete the ports on a subnet/network deletion, the active plugin's delete_port method will never be called. This is important (at least in some of the plugins) because it notifies a backend of a port removal."}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2013-10-09 17:29:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Kevin: If I understand you correctly, would it be possible to query the network's associated ports before the cascade and send the deletion event to the plugin for each port after the transaction commits?  Or is it necessary that the plugin be able to raise an exception on port deletion to roll back the transaction?"}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2013-10-09 17:37:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Maru: It needs to be able to raise an exception to roll back the transaction. If a connection to the plugin's back-end fails during a port removal and the exception doesn't rollback the transaction, we will end up with ports existing in the back-end that no longer exist in Neutron."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-10-09 18:31:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Maru, you know my position on leveraging capabilities from the dbms vs replicating them in the business logic: I agree with you that a CASCADE DELETE would be more suitable, but that's how it's been done so far and there's a distinction between fixing a race condition in time for the Havana release, and having an overhaul of the code that would most certainly require coordination amongst all the plugin maintainers and blueprints tracking. Besides, cascading port deletions on network delete won't solve the race because a concurrent subnet deletion will attempt to do a SET NULL on the subnet for port rows that are being deleted, so the SELECT FOR UPDATE will still need to be in place, at least on the subnet delete side."}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2013-10-09 21:12:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: No score

Fair enough.  Hopefully in the next release cycle we can stop with all this locking nonsense and instead work to ensure that operations are resilient in the face of competition.'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-10-09 21:36:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

The code itself looks good.
A question that I have not been able to answer myself is what would the impact of the failure deriving from this race condition. Does the dhcp agent crash? Does it trigger a full resync of the dhcp agent?
I'm asking this because I'm trying to understand if the impact is serious enough to grant a fix which locks the table for a potentially long transaction.

Scoring with -1 as agreed during last meeting.... not really, I'm scoring with -1 to piss off Armando, because I am pedant *and* evil!"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-10-09 23:23:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

The lock is per-row, actually.

As for the failure mode, the error is transient from what I have seen: you may get a failure on network delete, but if you try again the operation is successful. So I think the severity is not high (as I hinted during last IRC meeting).

As for the -1, you being my mentor, you must know that I am gonna take it very seriously...I am so hurt that I think I am handing my resignations :)'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-10-10 15:32:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (1 inline comment)

[{'created': '2013-09-13 19:53:49.000000000', 'message': 'Avoid dhcp agent race condition on subnet and network delete

This patch introduces the ability to set the lock mode
on a context. This allows to make queries aimed at
updating the state of the DB, thus solving potential
race conditions when multiple readers/writers are accessing
the DB, and yet keeping the transactional isolation
level down.

Fixes bug #1197627

Change-Id: I5bd75a758395a2faeff9db35a03c42dfa8ae0eab
'}, {'created': '2013-09-13 19:59:02.000000000', 'message': "Avoid dhcp agent race condition on subnet and network delete

This patch introduces the ability to set the lock mode
on a context. This allows to make queries aimed at
updating the state of the DB, thus solving potential
race conditions when multiple readers/writers are accessing
the DB, and yet keeping the transactional isolation
level down.

NOTE: even though comments in openstack/common/.../session.py
advise against the use of with_lockmode('UPDATE'), there may be
circumstances where this is a necessary measure; with this addition
we allow more restrictive reads to avoid race conditions
on concurrent writes without the need of raising the transactional
level of the DB.

That said, the use of SELECT FOR UPDATE construct has been used a
few times in db_base_plugin_v2, so it seems like this is a sensible
approach. Whether these places should be refactored to use the new
context property is outside the scope of the patch and would need
consensus first.

Fixes bug #1197627

Change-Id: I5bd75a758395a2faeff9db35a03c42dfa8ae0eab

commit_message:
Avoid dhcp agent race condition on subnet and network delete

Ensure that ports that are about to be deleted are 'selected
for update'. By doing so, we avoid a race condition between
subnet and network delete operations carried out by two
separate server instances.

A race caused by the dhcp agent deleting the DHCP port
(caused by a subnet-delete event notification) can
still occur and will be addressed in a subsequent patch.

delete_subnet's way to delete ports has been tweaked to
ensure that postgres db can handle the SELECT FOR UPDATE
correctly.

Partial-Bug:1197627

Change-Id: I5bd75a758395a2faeff9db35a03c42dfa8ae0eab

[{'created': '2013-11-25 04:48:55.000000000', 'message': 'Protect against hashdir cleanups errors on PUTs

In http://launchpad.net/bugs/1254405 an exception occurs when
finalizing the PUT of an object, but it is obscured by the thread pool
code, so we don't see the actual line where it originated. However,
there are two possible functions where this exception could originate:

    1. renamer()
    2. hashdir_cleanup_listdir()

If this is an error in renamer(), there is some other waky problem
where the temporary file has been removed. It is likely that this is a
problem where a file name from os.listdir ends up disappearing (but
even this is a stretch). However, it is not clear that we really want
an error from hashdir_cleanup_listdir() from affecting the return
result of the PUT.

Even that we use "Closes-Bug" below, it is not clear it can even be
determined that this closes that bug report.

Change-Id: I2f55df835c387e4d17cffda74c04c9994aebbe1f
Closes-Bug: 1254405
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Protect against hash cleanup errors on PUTs

In http://launchpad.net/bugs/1254405 an exception occurs when
finalizing the PUT of an object, but it is obscured by the thread pool
code, so we don't see the actual line where it originated. However,
there are two possible functions where this exception could originate:

    1. renamer()
    2. hash_cleanup_listdir()

If this is an error in renamer(), there is some other waky problem
where the temporary file has been removed. It is likely that this is a
problem where a file name from os.listdir ends up disappearing (but
even this is a rare occurence). Regardless, it is not clear that we
really want an error from hash_cleanup_listdir() from affecting the
return result of the PUT.

To that end, we squelsh OSErrors from hash_cleanup_listdir() for
now. One might argue for all errors, but since os.unlink() and
os.listdir() raise OSError today, that is probably sufficient.

Even that we use "Closes-Bug" below, it is not clear it can even be
determined that this closes that bug report.

Change-Id: I2f55df835c387e4d17cffda74c04c9994aebbe1f
Closes-Bug: 1254405
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

commit_message:
use correct url on Windows platform

os.path.normpath is used to clean url. On windows platform, it
returns url with "\" instead of "/", which is required in heat api
 in:
/heat/heat/api/middleware/version_negotiation.py,
path_info_peek method.

Change-Id: Ic1a5fc5dd789a7996e08a85a9d8908267e203565
Closes-Bug: 1254657

(lockutils and rpc) usages of strong_store might be potentially
affected.

Closes-Bug: #1254046

commit_message:
Sync openstack.common.local from oslo

`local` has a broken TLS symbol - strong_store, fixed in oslo some time
ago in
Ib544be1485823f6c619312fdee5a04031f48bbb4. All direct and indirect
(lockutils and rpc) usages of strong_store might be potentially
affected.
Original change to Nova: If4dd973acc23921dbc2bc69bb76225deb2802dad

Change-Id: I6839c80c6153b2f4fd28579c33a1a029b8276702
Closes-Bug: #1254046

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary "is not None" check

From a review comment on https://review.openstack.org/30051 remove
the "is not None" check, as the assignment in the try block will
never assign None as value as the int() built-in will not return it.

There was some concern of long-term maintenance of the DiskFile
class's _quarantine method raising exceptions. If that routine were
ever mistakenly changed to NOT raise an exception, subtle problems
could creep into the code (see https://review.openstack.org/53237).
We address this concern by raising an exception explicitly at the
call sites of DiskFile._quarantine().

Change-Id: I1729a2d77a6b72b4494b24a8838b47ad5272c075
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

commit_message:
test: improve db_replicator coverage

This patch adds a test for ReplicatorRpc.complete_rsync()
and complete extract_device() coverage.

test_extract_device:
  test the case the parameter is invalid

test_complete_rsync_with_bad_input:
  ensure the use of invalid parameters return a 404 erro

test_complete_rsync:
  validate the returned code in case of success

Change-Id: I59e0d26a1efe59d8beff1e81c2a7edc6de0872e9

commit_message:
Remove received reviews from output.

Remove the number of reviews received from the reviewers report output.
I think this information is valuable, but the values we're getting are
not accurate.  The problem is that if a patch gets rebased, the trivial
rebase detection will automatically re-apply reviews.  Those are getting
counted even though they aren't new reviews being received.

Change-Id: I3f1c620c225c1d1d3f2a137b095bac847a353238

commit_message:
Use fixtures for all shell environment variables

Currently only the variables related to the test are set, so
any other OS_* variables in the local environment can affect
the test results leading to confusing results.  Setting all
variables not passed into fake_env to None will delete them
in the fixture, hence ensuring a consistent test environment.

Change-Id: I24a07ef5fc89ca9fff121fe206b8e314f23c4402

commit_message:
Cleanup exc.verbose after tests

A couple of tests override the (module level) exc.verbose flag,
but fail to reset it after the test, which leads to failures
if a test expecting non-verbose exception format happens after the
verbose test.

Change-Id: Iac633707e74464f8d6509a0c5aa0cc62da00ce47

commit_message:
Pass only tenant name or ID to keystoneclient

When creating the keystoneclient, we only need to pass the tenant
ID or name, not both

Change-Id: I0dd03759979026daba1be343f7194f9b7e15a589

commit_message:
Fedora/RHEL DB updates for devstack_gate.sh

If you're using Fedora or Red Hat in your jenkins server,
It will always fail when check the database, because
on Fedora, the path for postgres and mysql directories
are different from Ubuntu.
This will check which distro are being used and check
the right path.

Change-Id: Ib1df1c9be92ce5a506caa5b36b69dfab32d9a99f

'}, {'account_id': 8414, 'date': '2013-11-25 21:57:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Some context for this bug fix:
- this bug occures when resource was replaced during stack updating 
- method create() of class Resource calls stack.resolve_static_data(self.json_snippet) to ensure that  AWS::StackId pseudo parameter referenced correctly.
- This fix added call of _set_param_stackid to method resolve_static_data. This ensures that stack id has correct value.

If someone has better solution, please let me know.

Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 6794, 'date': '2013-11-26 09:46:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Alexander,

1/ Have you tested that the change fixes the issue? I don't understand how your patch would work since _set_param_stackid() is already called in the __init__() method of the Stack class.
2/ Writing a unit test will be required eventually so it might better to start with it.
3/ I think the fix should rather be done in the update_stack() method of the EngineService class.

Thanks for the efforts"}, {'account_id': 7135, 'date': '2013-11-26 10:35:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

The root cause is here, https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/parser.py#L488. The newstack doesn't have an id - it isn't stored. So unlike the usual cause where the AWS::StackId param is overrided again in Stack.store, its AWS::StackId param is only initialized once during its init phase to a value with none at the end, https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/common/identifier.py#L121.

So an alternative solution would be to call _set_param_stackid again after https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/parser.py#L488 to ensure an updated stack still has the right AWS::StackId param."}, {'account_id': 8414, 'date': '2013-11-26 10:58:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

to Simon
Yes, I have tested this fix. Of course I'll add the test. Thanks for your notes.
to Liang
You have described bug context much better then I. Thanks!
The idea to add the fix to https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/parser.py#L488 seems good for me. Thanks again!

I'll rewrite and retest the patch and add unit test for this case."}, {'account_id': 8414, 'date': '2013-11-26 12:48:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Work In Progress'}, {'account_id': 8414, 'date': '2013-11-27 13:09:49.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-27 13:48:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Fix not correct AWS::StackId value

Add call of method _set_param_stackid() to method update_task() in class
parser.Stack. This ensures that an updated stack still has the right
AWS::StackId param.
Add a unit test for this case.

Change-Id: I0d28346631546577a85735292a24c2512476d4b4
Closes-Bug: #1240888

commit_message:
Allow alarm-threshold-update to upate generic attributes

Fixes bug 1253989

Previously, generic (i.e. non-threshold-related) alarm attributes could
not be updated with the alarm-threshold-update command. An attempt to
do so failed semi-silently when a non-existent dict key was referenced.

Now, all alarm attributes can be updated with this command.

Change-Id: Iba3f21de879fb853575dcec1730de7873eab8afd

commit_message:
Add a unit test to verify proxy logging fields

reported as "covered").

commit_message:
Remove the redundant judgment for 'restore'

In the function 'restore', there is redundant judgment for the body, it
should be removed.

Change-Id: Icfc5ae20141fad9d72de227cf5c06ca8504bd22c
Closes-Bug: 1254671
