'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-09-11 04:25:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Man, I'm torn on this one.  There's sort of two changes going on here, and I have different feelings about them.

I think the change of not calling sleep when using multiple threads per disk is actually much more interesting than moving the responsibility of not starving the eventlet hub from the wsgi layer to diskfile.  When using threads_per_disk I'm able to realize a couple more requests per second on a simple swift-bench test.  NICE!

OTOH, I sorta had an idea that the diskfile might not need to care if the wsgi layer was running eventlet with threads, or relying on multiple processes, or whatever.  I think parameterizing threadpool made a good separation barrier and a simple contract for diskfile:

"If you make blocking calls you must do them in the passed in threadpool's run_in_thread."

I had hoped that diskfile implementors wouldn't need to know any more than that to do the right thing.  I don't *what* to say about force_run_in_thread :\

Knowing when to call eventlet's sleep so as not to starve out the outer loop calling into you depending on the value of an attribute on the passed in threadpool - certainly seems to push a bit more earnest to do the right thing into diskfile.

The wsgi layer really has the better knowledge about the configuration of the environment to know *how* blocking calls should be handled, and that's why *it* creates the threadpool and hands it to diskfile.  The ObjectController could almost as easily do the nthreads check with the assumption that unless it gave a non-blocking threadpool to diskfile - write in a tight loop might be blocking and I need to sleep to avoid potential unfairness to *my* clients.  That's an unfortunate assumption if you have a diskfile who's write method will never (or even rarely) block (maybe it's buffering, or shared memory, or already green) then it would certainly *not* be calling 'run_in_thread' (at least not on the iterations when it's doing non-blocking work) - and the wsgi layer may miss an opportunity to optimize out a sleep call here and there (but only when threads_per_disk is turned off, with threads_per_disk it can trust the diskfile to do the right thing).

What about moving the sleep call into threadpool?!  If diskfile calls "run_in_thread" - but the damn wsgi layer gave it a threadpool thats translating those and running them inline - maybe before the threadpool returns, it should sleep!

It'd be a slightly more nuanced change because of the quarantine renamer and get_data_file_size - which probably don't strictly *need* to sleep since they're not in a tight call loop - but I think at least in the case of __iter__ it sorta lines up with the direction we want head anyway.

Maybe a more blunt approach would be to let the ObjectController call into threadpool when it's in a tight loop and say "I'm about to continue in a tight loop, so if your run_in_thread method was called but I've neutered it - please make a yield for me".  Probably have to use a threadlocal :\

Dunno... Optimizing for non-blocking diskfiles is a good thing, but I don't know if this bit of responsibility makes for a good implementation story for diskfile when it already has that threadpool param.  Why'd we give it a threadpool if using it isn't good enough?'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-09-11 18:04:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@clayg

> The wsgi layer really has the better knowledge about the configuration of the environment to know *how* blocking calls should be handled, and that's why *it* creates the threadpool and hands it to diskfile.

So are we saying we want the REST API layer to know about blocking
calls and/or how behaviors are implemented in the DiskFile class?
Perhaps we want a contract with the DiskFile class that it is
cooperative under eventlet hub environments. And then, the fact that
the WSGI layer creates thread pools appears to be yet another internal
implementation detail that is exposed, and perhaps one that should be
pushed into the DiskFile class itself.

I'll propose something in another commit.

> The ObjectController could almost as easily do the nthreads check with the assumption that unless it gave a non-blocking threadpool to diskfile - write in a tight loop might be blocking and I need to sleep to avoid potential unfairness to *my* clients. That's an unfortunate assumption if you have a diskfile who's write method will never (or even rarely) block (maybe it's buffering, or shared memory, or already green) then it would certainly *not* be calling 'run_in_thread' (at least not on the iterations when it's doing non-blocking work) - and the wsgi layer may miss an opportunity to optimize out a sleep call here and there (but only when threads_per_disk is turned off, with threads_per_disk it can trust the diskfile to do the right thing).

Do you mean to say that we should keep the checks to need for sleep in
one place?

> What about moving the sleep call into threadpool?! If diskfile calls "run_in_thread" - but the damn wsgi layer gave it a threadpool thats translating those and running them inline - maybe before the threadpool returns, it should sleep!

Not a bad idea, I'll try that instead.

> It'd be a slightly more nuanced change because of the quarantine renamer and get_data_file_size - which probably don't strictly *need* to sleep since they're not in a tight call loop - but I think at least in the case of __iter__ it sorta lines up with the direction we want head anyway.

If I understand the reason for the sleep correctly, tight loops are
not the problem, but that it is possible for code paths to exist which
will not enter the eventlet hub, thus preventing a trampoline
operation to another greenlet. Uncooperative code paths.

Perhaps we want to stipulate that a given DiskFile implementation
works cooperatively with the eventlet hub employed by the REST API
layer? It seems like a reasonable thing to do even outside of this one
path with the sleep call on it.'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-09-11 18:25:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-11 19:04:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Works for me

Commit dependency is unnecessary, but if Peter wants his patch to be held up in the queue unnecessarily, then who am I to judge.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-10-31 00:58:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

I dunno, I sort of like having the fairness stuff in the object server. The background daemons don't really run with multiple greenlets, so they don't really have to worry about fairness, but the object server has greenlets and has code to ensure fairness.

Is the concern here the iter_hook parameter to DiskFile.reader? If that's objectionable, I think that'd be pretty easy to get rid of with some kind of wrapper iterator thingy."}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-10-31 18:25:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

@Sam, what other fairness does the object server perform once we move the sleep calls down into ThreadPools?'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-10-31 19:09:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

I was thinking that it would be harder to accidentally break if the cooperative sleeps were textually contained in the object server code.

I tried writing an explicit iterator-wrapper that I thought might work okay, but it turned out to be a real pain in my ass. Getting it to work for normal GET requests is okay, but the interaction between the DiskFileReader and swob is pretty complicated (look for "app_iter_range"), and wrapping all that up turned into a giant pile of garbage (http://paste.openstack.org/show/50325/ in case you're curious).

I guess this approach is good enough, then... I don't think there's a way to get a result from a real worker thread without going through a greenlet switch, if only because there's a greenlet responsible for pulling events off the queue.'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-11-19 20:47:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 15.'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2013-11-19 20:53:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

[{'created': '2013-09-03 15:27:52.000000000', 'message': 'Push sleep call down into DiskFileWriter.write()

commit_message:
Push cooperative sleep call down into ThreadPool

The PUT REST API has no idea how writes are performed, so when thread
pools are in use, the sleep is not necessary, though it is still
necessary when thread pools are not in use. Since the ThreadPool
object knows when threads are actually in use, it can take care of
being cooperative with the eventlet hub.

In addition, we can hide the cooperative iterator hook, given that the
only other consumer of this was the auditor, which does not need it
any longer.  The only consumer of the DiskFile class that wants the
cooperative behavior is the REST API layer of the object server, which
is also using thread pools.

Change-Id: Ibc4ac672899f9a35fd68c85d7f56403c19b4f991
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Report path information in failure exceptions

When an error occurs during functional tests that use the
swift_test_client module, the reported error message includes the
method and path:

    ResponseError: 500: 'Internal Error' ('HEAD' \
    '/v1/AUTH_test/d5ce...')

Change-Id: I631cd9e83879fb644778d4ded62625483bf38045

As a cluster operator, I don't particularly want all my config details being made public.

As a client, I don't care one tiny bit if proxy_logging or memcache or catch_errors are enabled. I don't see any benefit to having that stuff in there at all, though I'd be okay with either making it admin-only or omitting it entirely.

There may be other middlewares that should be omitted from the public /info response too; these are just the ones that jumped out at me on my SAIO.

I took the liberty of making some changes here; if you object, just run "git review" from your branch, and it'll push a patch set 8 that's equivalent to patch set 6, and I'll take a hint and go away. :)

BIG CHANGE: I turned /info on by default. I think clients are going to find this incredibly useful, and it shouldn't be a setting that admins have to remember to opt into. It's not like it'll generate any appreciable load on the cluster; it's just the proxy serving up a small JSON blob from memory.

Other changes here are basically what I had pointed out in review comments:
 * SLO's register_swift_info was in the wrong spot
 * DELETE /info was nonsense; only allow GET/HEAD
 * docstring needed fixing post-move
 * needed a sane way of generating the signed /info URL + docs for it

Like I said above, if you disagree, please feel free to revert my changes and tell me to take a flying leap. I'm just excited for this feature, so I want to get it in sooner rather than later.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-21 01:46:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Doesn't seem to work

or, if this gets versioned like I think it should,

  /v1/info/

to be considered a "Bad URL" instead of just working?

Unlike most of the rest of the Swift API, there aren't additional, optional segments separated by slashes.  OTOH, maybe allowing one endpoint to allow a trailing slash would be confusing because it's not consistent.'}, {'account_id': 2696, 'date': '2013-11-25 23:16:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: No score

commit_message:
Added discoverable capabilities.

Swift can now optionally be configured to allow requests to '/info',
providing information about the swift cluster.  Additionally a HMAC
signed requests to
'/info?swiftinfo_sig=<sign>&swiftinfo_expires=<expires>' can be
configured allowing privileged access to more sensitive information
not meant to be public.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I2379360fbfe3d9e9e8b25f1dc34517d199574495
Implements: blueprint capabilities
Closes-Bug: #1245694

commit_message:
HOT template to deploy chef server

Added a HOT template to deploy a server using Open Source CHEF.
The template uses the CHEF OmniTruck API to retrieve the latest
stable release of Open Source Chef Server. This is a single resource
template and is compatible with Ubuntu as well as CentOS/RHEL.

Change-Id: I407f0666fa269044ba7d07caa9a0dab59ffdb936

commit_message:
Add heatclient to available clients

The first resource to use this will need to ensure
that this method has test coverage. There appears to be
no convention for writing separate unit tests for these
client methods.

This will currently not work with standalone heat as
the heat endpoint will not be in the keystone catalog, see
related-bug: #1255713

partial blueprint: hot-software-config
Change-Id: I9e793190a28dd7cb351c8c6cdb3b824b6e5ecd1a

commit_message:
Implement consistent hashing common methods

Implement consistent hashing functions and add unit tests.

These will be used by each conductor service to determine
which nodes it is responsible for, and by each API service
to determine where to route RPC requests for specific nodes.

Change-Id: I6d6ae987e76e2d11f8f3f8843800a17d8ff1aaa0
bp: instance-mapping-by-consistent-hash

Note that these were for grizzly (we're still catching up).

I'd appreciate some more clarity about what's in and out, if you have a moment."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-11-25 16:03:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

That patch/blueprint was merged, yes.  This is about the existing snapshot command being able to work without having to stop or pause the VM.  There are no new commands added with this.  The docs seem to mix this up with another feature that was being proposed but was not merged.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-11-25 22:31:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

If you think some of the changes might be still applicable, could you update the patch so that it *only* includes real changes?  It looks like some sections are changing without any text changes, and that makes it harder to review'}, {'account_id': 67, 'date': '2013-11-25 22:58:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

There seems to be a bit of confusion around the term "live-snapshots". The description used here fits with the code I attempted to merge during the last cycle which refers to a snapshot of a virtual machine which includes processor and memory state. The intention was that these could be used to create "clones" of a running virtual machine. This feature was abandoned due to security concerns.

The referenced bug comes from a commit which has a different meaning for live snapshot (which probably should have been called no-downtime snapshots). It is a feature that allows users to snapshot running virtual machines without pausing them. These snapshots are simply disk-only snapshots.

The documentation about this feature should be something relatively simple stating that while snapshotting an instance previously would pause the instance while the snapshot was being performed, they can now be performed with no downtime (assuming qemu 1.3+ and libvirt 1.0+ are being used.'}, {'account_id': 8047, 'date': '2013-11-27 04:27:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-27 04:37:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

commit_message:
Add Live snapshots section to Ops Guide

Implements support for live snapshots, new nova feature, when QEMU 1.3 and Libvirt 1.0.0 are available
Edits grammar and style in surrounding sections
Needs further stylistic edits to listings and headings to match other guides

Change-Id: I07283f02d59877465faadfc74079fa9757dc4390
author: nermina miller
Closes-Bug: #1111093

commit_message:
Bugfix: Fix fragment name for Quota middleware

  Bugfix for commit 4157cb9 (uniformisation of pipeline names)
  According other swift proxy middlewares, the concat fragments
    doesn't contains « proxy » (concat frag. are generated by pipeline)
    see l195 and l196 of tests/site.pp

Change-Id: I99f9e5f5282b3e8db89fd56109ec8074ea1fa8f5

Replace get_rec* with get_uuid or equivalent when retrieving a single
value from XAPI.  This removes a significant overhead in the get_rec calls

Change-Id: Ie2370f5c4ff81ceb62224c5bcf7418d29a8921a3
'}]
commit_message:
XenAPI: Speedup calls for single value

Replace get_rec* with get_uuid or equivalent when retrieving a single
value from XAPI.  This removes a significant overhead in the get_rec calls

Change-Id: Ie2370f5c4ff81ceb62224c5bcf7418d29a8921a3

commit_message:
Bad except clauses order causes wrong text in http response

InstanceInvalidState is an ancestor class of InstanceIsLocked, so
we need to catch InstanceIsLocked first. Fix the test case to
ensure we get the right http response back

Change-Id: Id22b284d9b7da8db4161ad8703bea1702cb0b82e

commit_message:
Account for a platform difference in semaphores

On OS X (and probably other Operating Systems) it isn't possible to
introspect the value of a semaphore. Account for this by skipping a
test about this.

Change-Id: I97824f9fc4e36de4f7a62c8ce53865e6977dfdfe

commit_message:
rst-xml-conversion revisited

we likely will be using most of the developer reference material in
the developer training guide. there is good tidbits of information like
what is patched here. as it gets included, some reformating will get pushed
back into the cinder project. like the architecture asc art will get either
converted into a diagram or add a flag for an xml programlisting tag. rst files
in the devref source, but not converted to xml will get patched in cinder
for update or removal.

implements blueprint rst-xml-conversion

Change-Id: Ib4a577a77d0d19e1864860c6940a46cbb11b2028

commit_message:
Add auto-generated solum.conf.sample

Add a script that automatically generates solum.conf.sample.  Include
the initial config sample.  This should be updated every time an option
is added, changed, or removed.  We can add an automatic check for this
at some point, as well.

Change-Id: Iace8c4a3c5b63f5f3808e5bb725b23086bf3d840

commit_message:
Reorganize SLO unit tests

This brings some sanity to the SLO test app (the thing the middleware
wraps in the unit tests) as well as splits things into multiple test
classes.

This is part of the effort to move all SLO functionality to
middleware, but it's a separate commit to prove that these test
changes don't harm anything when running against the old code.

Change-Id: I52a16f15a80dfaf9b3c595b0e634d52f418caf6c

commit_message:
Check HTTP response headers of Swift API in detail

All HTTP response headers for each Swift API are checked their existence
and style. For checking, create custom_matchers.py file in common directory
and implement specific matchers so that they can be reused.

Change-Id: I7dcd87c814cf657999796bda75482505112b4edb
Closes-Bug: #1240856

commit_message:
Lower severity of log trace for DB integrity error

LOG.exception is not appropriate, since a concurrent
port creation can occur and it has been dealt with
in the except block.

This avoids spooking users who are on the hunt for
real bugs.

Supports fix for 1239637

Change-Id: I9489702ee63db0b004fe41195fa4727af261d514
(cherry picked from commit 4c6906498a5ef0f11ada3ff2224e995f6b3062d8)

commit_message:
port test_simple_tenant_usage into nova v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I0ef1d85fe7ce7e9ca836c6e3a5a447df9941eccd

commit_message:
port attach_interfaces and server_address tests into v3 part2

This port interface client into v3 and the attach_interface tests
into v3, also port server_address tests into v3

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I0701ace05c6ae7feb72a6a00949ae830f63ff853

commit_message:
Use TCP_NODELAY for created sockets.

Mark Seger at HP has been looking at small objects, 1 and 2 KB size,
and with Rick Jones' help noticed that TCP protocol traces showed
effects from the Nagel algorithm client-to-server and
server-to-client.

This patch just addresses our WSGI server responses, but does not
address out-bound connections from the various servers.

Change-Id: I11f86df1f56fba1c6ab6084dc1f580c395f072dc
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Throttle tripleo-cd.sh

Prevent tripleo-cd.sh from spamming IRC channels when it encounters an
error that happens early in the devtest_overcloud.sh story by throttling
it to running at most once every 10 minutes.

Change-Id: I703eb5ca5525eff97a6925cfe2c585f8908798c5

integrate the cfn collector into a heat template. This info could

starting point.

'}]
commit_message:
Import uuidutils unit tests from oslo

uuidutils is going to be removed from oslo, so we need to remove the
calls from our Ironic code. For reference, see
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-November/018980.html

This change imports the unit tests from Oslo for both
generate_uuid and is_uuid_like, which have been ported to ironic.common.

Closes-Bug: #1253497
Change-Id: I14ed5864615d798f5658d53be28af6bd5e86fc43

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-19 17:44:28.000000000', 'message': 'Added check on plugin.supported_extension_aliases

Adds check to neutron.api.extensions.PluginAwareExtensionManager
which raises an exception for a common class of bugs in plugins:
typographical errors in the `supported_extension_aliases` property.
Also, added and updated unit tests.

Plugin changes:

* bigswitch.plugin: Moves api_extensions_path override to plugin's
__init__ method, similar to other plugins.

* cisco.n1kv.n1kv_neutron_plugin: Removes "policy_profile_binding" and
"network_profile_binding" as they don't exist in Neutron currently.
Extended override of api_extensions_path to append cisco extensions
path to existing configured path.

* cisco.network_plugin: Renames "Cisco Credential" to "credential".
Adds api_extension_path override to plugin's __init__ method.

* metaplugin.meta_neutron_plugin: Avoids alias of empty string when
cfg.CONF.META.supported_extension_aliases is an empty string.

* midonet.plugin: Fixes regression from 715b16ac.

* nec.nec_plugin: Extended override of api_extensions_path to append
nec extensions path to existing configured path.

* nicira.NeutronPlugin: Extended override of api_extensions_path to
append NXP_EXT_PATH to existing configured path.

Fixes: bug 1225080

Change-Id: Idcaade221d83c611fcbd87b503b2c8377d106962
'}, {'created': '2013-09-19 20:54:04.000000000', 'message': 'Added check on plugin.supported_extension_aliases

Added check to neutron.api.extensions.PluginAwareExtensionManager
which raises an exception when an alias in the plugin's
supported_extension_alias list is not found in the set of loaded
extension aliases. If an alias is missing, it means the extension for
that alias has not been found and has not been loaded. This guards
against a common class of bugs in plugins, typographical errors in
the `supported_extension_aliases` property. Also, added and updated
unit tests.

Plugin changes:

* bigswitch.plugin: Moves api_extensions_path override to plugin's
__init__ method, similar to other plugins.

* cisco.n1kv.n1kv_neutron_plugin: Removes "policy_profile_binding" and
"network_profile_binding" as they don't exist in Neutron currently.
Extended override of api_extensions_path to append cisco extensions
path to existing configured path.

* cisco.network_plugin: Renames "Cisco Credential" to "credential".
Adds api_extension_path override to plugin's __init__ method.

* metaplugin.meta_neutron_plugin: Avoids alias of empty string when
cfg.CONF.META.supported_extension_aliases is an empty string.

* midonet.plugin: Fixes regression from 715b16ac.

* nec.nec_plugin: Extended override of api_extensions_path to append
nec extensions path to existing configured path.

* nicira.NeutronPlugin: Extended override of api_extensions_path to
append NXP_EXT_PATH to existing configured path.

Fixes: bug 1225080

Change-Id: Idcaade221d83c611fcbd87b503b2c8377d106962
'}, {'created': '2013-09-19 21:02:16.000000000', 'message': 'Added check on plugin.supported_extension_aliases

Added check to neutron.api.extensions.PluginAwareExtensionManager
which raises an exception when an alias in the plugin's
`supported_extension_aliases` list is not found in the set of loaded
extension aliases. If an alias is missing, it means the extension for
that alias has not been loaded, has not been found, and the file is
missing from paths listed in `oslo.config.CONF.api_extension_path`.

This guards against a common class of bugs in plugins,
such as typographical errors in the `supported_extension_aliases`
property.

commit_message:
Added check on plugin.supported_extension_aliases

Added check to neutron.api.extensions.PluginAwareExtensionManager
which raises an exception when an alias in the plugin's
`supported_extension_aliases` list is not found in the set of loaded
extension aliases. If an alias is missing, it means the extension for
that alias has not been loaded, has not been found, and the file is
missing from paths listed in `oslo.config.CONF.api_extensions_path`.

This guards against a common class of bugs in plugins,
such as typographical errors in the `supported_extension_aliases`
property.

Plugin changes:

* bigswitch.plugin: Moves api_extensions_path override to plugin's
__init__ method, similar to other plugins.

* cisco.n1kv.n1kv_neutron_plugin: Removes "policy_profile_binding" and
"network_profile_binding" as they don't exist in Neutron currently.
Removed override of api_extensions_path as it is loaded through
cisco.network_plugin.

* cisco.network_plugin: Renames "Cisco Credential" to "credential".
Adds api_extension_path override to plugin's __init__ method.

* metaplugin.meta_neutron_plugin: Avoids alias of empty string when
cfg.CONF.META.supported_extension_aliases is an empty string.

* midonet.plugin: Fixes regression of 98e16a06 from 715b16ac.

* nec.nec_plugin: Extended override of api_extensions_path to append
nec extensions path to existing configured path.

* nicira.NeutronPlugin: Extended override of api_extensions_path to
append NXP_EXT_PATH to existing configured path.

Fixes: bug 1225080

Change-Id: Idcaade221d83c611fcbd87b503b2c8377d106962

commit_message:
Rebind security groups only when they're updated

Update the security port bindings for a port only when they actually
differ from the stored value.

This will also avoid sending port_update notifications to the agent
even if nothing actually changes in the port configuration.

Closes-Bug: #1255183
Partial blueprint: neutron-tempest-parallel

Change-Id: I00c29dc97c46478433fdf08069a884bb78e5cd0a

commit_message:
VMware: Detach volume should not delete vmdk

During volume detach a delete_virtual_disk_spec is used to remove
the device from the running instance. This spec also "destroy" the
underlying vmdk file, this is not right, we should not delete vmdk
file when detach it from a VM instance.

The fix was remove the fileOperation field when detach vmdk volume
so as to make sure the volume will not be destroyed; but for iscsi
we still need to destroy the volume.

Also I changed the function name from delete_virtual_disk_spec to
detach_virtual_disk_spec which is more accurate.

Change-Id: Ibd218d6a8cfeede4f5ca74f28bc0c3d0c185bb14
Closes-Bug: #1241350
(cherry picked from commit 0405d7b937fdeece46efc1ba90171163f3286a56)

commit_message:
Mocking ryu plugin notifier in ryu plugin test

Previously RPC notifier is not mocked in ryu plugin test and the
plugin tries to send RPC notifications. It may interact with
impl_fake RPC set up in previous tests by other plugin
and sometimes leads to unexpected ovs-vsctl invoking.

Change-Id: I11714a160faa4d3ded7f312c39afba0b426ccd8a
Closes-Bug: #1255421

commit_message:
Simplify the dispatcher method prototype

`record_metering_data' is receiving a context that is never used in the
dispatch drivers. So let's remove it to simplify our code and
interfaces.

Change-Id: I811fe86b86749de4c4d52a57e761021604f7b818

commit_message:
Some functional tests for static large objects

There's some sort-of-hacky code in there to detect SLO support in
order to skip tests when SLO is off so that the functests won't fail
on older clusters.

Change-Id: I6ad5974a0db7213747b0f4497d08ffc706d3f220

commit_message:
There is really no problem with this change. However, it is probably triggering a port_update notification to the agent for each port with an allocated IP.

The agent handles that notification in a way which might be improved from scalability perspective.

I don't actually want this change to removed, I am just checking whether neutron without it passess jobs.

Related-Bug: 1253896

Revert "ML2 plugin should not delete ports on subnet deletion"

This reverts commit 0d131ff0e9964cb6a65f64809270f9d597c2d5d1

commit_message:
Add HTML reporting for test branch coverage.

When including branch coverage results, also generate HTML reports into
a "cover" subdirectory under the directory in which .unittests resides
(i.e. known location at the top of the swift tree).

Change-Id: I493d74f38755f7bf0d7043052585efb27840b238

commit_message:
Do not format messages before they are logged

The python logging facility allows for the logging message to contain
string formatting commands, and will format that string with any
additional arguments provided. It will only perform this formatting if
the logging level allows.

So if you have:

   A. logging.debug("this %s that %s", this, that)
   B. logging.debug("this %s that %s" % (this, that))

Then A only formats the message if the debug logging level is set,
where as B will always format the message. Since this filter is often
on the fast-path for swift requests, it will help the small object
case to avoid any extra possible work.

Change-Id: I51414dc6577df50d5573a0f917e0656c4ae99520

commit_message:
Fix bug in obj updater run_once().

The "not" in front of the ismount() call got accidentally dropped in a
recent change.  This patch adds it back along with a few more tests.

Note that this bug only showed up on an SAIO during probe tests because
I used actually-mounted (virtual) "disks".  So keep that in mind when
building SAIOs for development/testing.

Change-Id: Ia193f3c4b73203605954036863575c22ddab6b03

[{'created': '2013-10-30 12:56:09.000000000', 'message': 'Pass volume_api to get_encryption_metadata

The module encryptors was creating a volume API instance in the module
scope which caused all the modules importing it to depend on
cinderclient.

This was affecting scheduler and cert services which at some point import
the compute manager module only to access their config options. It makes
no sense to force scheduler and cert services to require cinderclient.

This patch makes the callers of get_encryption_metadata to pass the
volume api object to this method to prevent this dependency.

Closes-Bug: #1246103
Change-Id: I9eb4ae3754fa2a5ac646560a62477d6ed672e272
(cherry picked from commit a3aeace9afd5c533f040452f33482fdb55d93927)
'}]
commit_message:
Pass volume_api to get_encryption_metadata

The module encryptors was creating a volume API instance in the module
scope which caused all the modules importing it to depend on
cinderclient.

This was affecting scheduler and cert services which at some point import
the compute manager module only to access their config options. It makes
no sense to force scheduler and cert services to require cinderclient.

This patch makes the callers of get_encryption_metadata to pass the
volume api object to this method to prevent this dependency.

Closes-Bug: #1246103
Change-Id: I9eb4ae3754fa2a5ac646560a62477d6ed672e272
(cherry picked from commit a3aeace9afd5c533f040452f33482fdb55d93927)

commit_message:
Check for None when cleaning PCI dev usage

The PCI manager needs to check for instance UUIDs mapped to
None when cleaning up it's internal claims/allocations maps.

Also adds a check so the claims dict doesn't map to None in
the first place.  There was already a check like this when
setting a value in the allocations dict.

Closes-Bug: #1238374

Change-Id: I7ac010f7d50ad85c145e536cfd48e07c8f4602d3
(cherry picked from commit c28c87db4c2b20e0f6c1375d2d4433e06c4e1743)

commit_message:
Add new attributes for common rpc configuration

We need provide ability to configure the following rpc related
attributes:
rpc_thread_pool_size
rpc_conn_pool_size
rpc_response_timeout
There is the similar changes on cinder:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/58189/

Change-Id: I93765f798b4c74727b8e4e962749e37468080c35

[{'created': '2013-11-15 17:51:02.000000000', 'message': 'refactor: drop simplejson requirement

After much benchmarking, it was decided that it is preferable to
remove the simplejson dependency. This comes with the caveat that json
handling is slower on Python<=2.6, but faster on Python>2.7, including
Python 3 and pypy.

The recommendation moving forward is to deploy Marconi on Python>2.7.

Change-Id: If7a9380bd32023ec973fd2f267255723aaa49306
'}]
commit_message:
refactor: drop simplejson requirement

After much benchmarking, it was decided that it is preferable to
remove the simplejson dependency. This comes with the caveat that json
handling is slower on Python<=2.6, but faster on Python>2.7, including
Python 3 and pypy.

The recommendation moving forward is to deploy Marconi on Python>2.7.

Change-Id: If7a9380bd32023ec973fd2f267255723aaa49306

commit_message:
If running git clean after reset then retry

* devstack-vm-gate-wrap.sh: If a git clean can not remove some
files, for example because a previous command has not freed its open
file handles, it will return nonzero. If this happens, wait a moment
and try again in case this is only a briefly transient problem.

Change-Id: I40ca9784f5e6e8bad07416f4fd1978bc7aecd494

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-15 17:12:23.000000000', 'message': 'Verify for duplicate location+metadata instances

Glance allow users to have duplicated locations for the same image. This
could led to some confusion and bad UX. This patch introduces such check
in the insert method and makes both extend and append use it to add new
images.

The patch also adds a new exception - DuplicateLocation - and handles it
in the v2 of the API. When `DuplicateLocation` is raised, a BadRequest
will be returned back to the client.

A new test for this functionality was added as well.

Change-Id: I32400d467408e3d56bbbdbb3379357f2ee812e56
Closes-bug: 1251244

commit_message:
Verify for duplicate location+metadata instances

Glance allow users to have duplicated locations for the same image. This
could led to some confusion and bad UX. This patch introduces such check
in the insert method and makes both extend and append use it to add new
images.

The patch also adds a new exception - DuplicateLocation - and handles it
in the v2 of the API. When `DuplicateLocation` is raised, a BadRequest
will be returned back to the client.

A new test for this functionality was added as well.

Change-Id: I32400d467408e3d56bbbdbb3379357f2ee812e56
Closes-bug: 1251244

commit_message:
Fix for tests failing on ::Chef::Application.fatal!

ChefSpec no longer does require 'chef' in an effort to speed up. This means that
the ::Chef::Application.fatal! calls in cookbooks started failing tests.

Change-Id: Icfdf70441dc4b0aaa9c188f5a2830fdfcc7b2953

commit_message:
Make check more pythonic

Use 'if key in ('metadata', 'system_metadata'):'
instead of 'if key == 'metadata' or key == 'system_metadata''

The reason for the change is:
1. The issue has come up more than once in review cycles
2. It is easier to read

Moving forwards it may be useful if there are extra use cases.

Change-Id: Icd4ab4ebd021720b140f9fdb89d201781388c8ff

commit_message:
Avoid intermittent integrity error on alarm creation

Fixes bug 1255107

Previously, alarm creation failed intermittently with the
sqlalchemy driver, due to the reliance on session merge to create
the project & user IDs if not already encountered.  This approach
conflicted with the strict foreign key constraints that were
added to the alarms table as an after-thought.

Now, we avoid the potential problem by explicitly creating the
project and user IDs if necessary.

Unfortunately, this cannot be tested via the scenario tests,
as there we use sqlite (the problematic migration does not
apply the foreign key constraints for that engine).

Change-Id: Ieaed676a0a68725242fadbf658646b874d6851ce

commit_message:
slightly less early quorum

The early quorum change has maybe added a little bit too much
eventual to the consistency of requests in Swift, and users can
sometimes get unexpected
results.

This change gives us a knob to turn in finding the right balance,
by adding a timeout where pending requests can finish after quorum
is achieved.

Change-Id: Ife91aaa8653e75b01313bbcf19072181739e932c

This version properly keeps track of pool size accounting, and

"}]
commit_message:
Use upstream patched Pool.get

This works around an eventlet bug in eventlet 0.9.16.
This version properly keeps track of pool size accounting, and
therefore doesn't let the pool grow without bound. This patched
version is the result of commit
f5e5b2bda7b442f0262ee1084deefcc5a1cc0694 in eventlet and is
documented at https://bitbucket.org/eventlet/eventlet/issue/91

This patch includes full test coverage of the back-ported code, even
when the actually-installed eventlet is newer.

This fixes bug #1254119

commit_message:
Fix DB locked error on commit

This bug was introduced in ef7f9e27; while moving timeout for execute
to the cursor wrapper, commit was moved as well; however commit is
purely a connection method, only execute is passed on to a cursor.
Added unit tests to check both methods for correct timeouts.

This manifested in a test failure as:
ERROR __call__ error with POST /sdb1/418/AUTH_d1c4b610b16a48de83219c696261009c/TestContainer-tempest-1572414684 :
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/opt/stack/new/swift/swift/container/server.py", line 486, in __call__
    res = method(req)
  File "/opt/stack/new/swift/swift/common/utils.py", line 1915, in wrapped
    return func(*a, **kw)
  File "/opt/stack/new/swift/swift/common/utils.py", line 687, in _timing_stats
    resp = func(ctrl, *args, **kwargs)
  File "/opt/stack/new/swift/swift/container/server.py", line 464, in POST
    broker.update_metadata(metadata)
  File "/opt/stack/new/swift/swift/common/db.py", line 677, in update_metadata
    conn.commit()
OperationalError: database is locked (txn: tx5065394f288740e69fcec-00528e184e)

Change-Id: I269b133fac53d4792d21b62f801cc0c0ccf337ea

When concurrent PUT requests come in for an account or container, the
resulting DB access will try to lock the DB for writing. Normal access
will retry when it encounters a locked DB, change 0fdad0d9 introduced

commit_message:
Fixed concurrent PUT requests to accounts or containers

When concurrent PUT requests come in for an account or container, the
resulting DB access will try to lock the DB for writing. Normal access
will retry when it encounters a locked DB, change 0fdad0d9 introduced
a cursor for doing the initialization which did not have the retry
capability, resulting in a hard failure.

Fixes bug 1243973

Change-Id: I73b219e0f5eacf314d87b4d5e56c03daf51b2eca

commit_message:
libvirt: Provide a port field for GlusterFS network disks

Some versions of libvirt (RHEL6's 0.10.2) require a port
specification with a GlusterFS network disk, or they reject
the disk with an "XML error: missing port for host" error.

Provide port 24007 as part of the disk specification.

Closes-Bug: #1254820

Change-Id: Iedcce32618813ed093b8e9aa8a69d1219b2118a5

commit_message:
Set boto minimum version

For supporting the S3 multipart upload in glance,
set boto minimum version to 2.12.0.

Implements: blueprint s3-multi-part-upload
Change-Id: Id57a3887256a665455fd83d3e8e752a28c5e7659

commit_message:
Adding qpid support to nova

Moving all qpid parameters under default["openstack"]["compute"]["mq"]["qpid"]
so that other qpid options can be added under it. Rabbit parameters
will be brought under "mq" eventually. Default is "rabbit".
Bumped up the minor version number from 7.1.0 to 7.2.0

Implements: blueprint qpid-activemq-support
Change-Id: Ie40b5a46a07ce12b7220efe9c4021252a1c6a1ce

"}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-11-26 23:31:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

White listing all neutron stack traces scares me a little. What is the motivation here?'}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-11-27 00:14:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Unless I made a mistake, this is not whitelisting neutron, it is un-whitelisting it. So all errors go in the log but the job is not failed. Maru suggested this.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-11-27 00:24:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

we are saying the same thing, 'Neutron will always return 0'  Which means we are whitelisting it even though the logs will say otherwise.  I still wonder what the benefit of this is."}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-11-27 02:55:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Maru asked if we could do this. I think the idea was to raise visibility of all the log errors given that we are not in a position to start failing neutron. For non-neutron we are getting close to being able to fail jobs. As to whether we also dump all the whitelisted errors into the log for non-neutron I could go either way. On balance it's probably better to not do that at least for now to make any new errors that start causing a failure to not be mixed in with the whitelisted errors."}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-11-27 15:53:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Dump all errors to console and special-case neutron

Neutron will always return 0.

commit_message:
Fix format errors seen in rpc logging

The previous commit for this bug didn't include the 'project_name'
key in the context dict.  The missing key was causing the amqp
module to generate log formatting exceptions instead of normal
log output.

Separately, the context module itself was generating logging
exceptions in the quantum service when logging was attempted
before the context was fully initialized

Change-Id: I0f4c6f5a6804442932c9b2bd409a258cfc2419ff
Closes-Bug: #1254530
Related-Bug: #1239923

commit_message:
Fixed a bug in sql migration script 020

In sql migration script 020_add_metadata_tables.py, the sql statements
to insert metadata from the meter table to the newly created tables
have never been executed.

Change-Id: I211e024ed8be65a19f670ce72e3035c8f8797a54

commit_message:
Network manager refactoring

It is a 1st step.

1. All class methods are @classmethods now and instantiating of class objects is removed.
2. There is a part independent from network type, Nova and Neutron parts are independent from each other.
3. Got rid from some unused code.

To be continued.

Implements: blueprint nailgun-network-manager-refactoring

Change-Id: I8d61a9acae995ff3e61f100a1d26dcc77df014a6

commit_message:
Improve timeout for dhcp response waiter

Dhcp checker tool is not always receives info
on dhcp servers in network
To make checking on network with 400 vlans it takes
7 min to perform
Also get_probing_info takes same time for this number of vlans

Change-Id: I03cac773030ccfd6c6f433e117ea9240d787bbbe
Closes-Bug: #1247284

Add openstack based server provider

Implement all base functionallity of OpenStack:
create_vms, destroy_vms - based on nova python client

blueprint vm-provider-openstack

commit_message:
Separate command to perform deploy and cleanup

The patch makes ready to use the EngineFactory in additional methods of
the orchestrations, e.g. create_deploy, destroy_deploy and
recreate_deploy. The cleanup should be an atomic operation to solve this
because it's needed only for two the last methods.

Change-Id: Id49bc8af0aba9e22a39749c60ac83e3c93471839
Implements: blueprint independent-deploy

use it for all javascript files.

commit_message:
JSHint integration

JSHint helps enforcing coding standards for the javascript files similarly to
pep8. It is integrated with the existing qUnit tests with the qhint library.
This approach has the advantage of running every time the selenium test suite
runs and does not introduce dependency to Node.js.

Partially implements: blueprint js-coding-style-checks

Change-Id: I77e75e7cdd5fd3426b9b981c4e0df5d30ef7b196

commit_message:
Separate provisioning and deployment handlers in nailgun api

* handler for provisioning selected nodes
  PUT /clusters/1/provision/?nodes=1,2,3
* handler for deployment selected nodes
  PUT /clusters/1/deploy/?nodes=1,2,3
* added nodes parameter for default deployment info
  GET /clusters/1/orchestrator/deployment/defaults/?nodes=1,2
* and added nodes parameter for default and provisioning info
  GET /clusters/1/orchestrator/provisioning/defaults/?nodes=1,2

Implements: blueprint nailgun-separate-provisioning-and-deployment-handlers
Change-Id: I2d6320fe15918f42c2071c62a65490cd7ad5d08c

Mac addresses in nailgun should be represented as lowercase string

commit_message:
Take pattern for logparsing by hostname instead of fqdn.
In naily logparser executes with provisioning data
not with deployment data as it was before.

Implemented: blueprint nailgun-separate-provisioning-and-deployment-handlers
Change-Id: I36a3663b22d4c6410f2904e3586be0b133978472

commit_message:
Switch sshutils.SSH from subprocess to paramiko

Methods for executing commands/scripts and upload
files to remote host via ssh of sshutils.SSH class
were rewritten using the paramiko lib.

Related: blueprint serverdto-ssh

Change-Id: I1786d5c4d4b6e9c661ec84785dd9255ab39de4aa

[{'created': '2013-11-19 21:02:47.000000000', 'message': 'Add SLDs that act like TLDs

This change is from the Icehouse release. The effective TLD file need
not be present. When it is not present the behavior would be the same
as before. When it is present, the domains that are being created are
checked to see that it is not an effective TLD.

This change offers the designate administrator the ability to configure
2 lists to indicate the TLDs(accepted_tlds_file) and SLDs and others
that effectively act as TLDs.(effective_tlds_file)

2 sample files are included to show the format required for these files.
The TLD file is from http://data.iana.org/TLD/tlds-alpha-by-domain.txt
Commented lines in this file begin with a #. There is one entry per line
and the entries are in the IDNA format.

The sample effective TLD file is from http://publicsuffix.org/list/
This file is in the UTF-8 format. Lines beginning with a // and ! are
ignored. The wildcard character * (asterisk) may only be used to
wildcard the topmost level in a domain name. All the entries are
converted to idna format.

Change-Id: I3d2f7e2741f4cda0b227e4a5671b141f99052291
Closes-Bug: #1249396

commit_message:
Add SLDs that act like TLDs

This change is from the Icehouse release. The effective TLD file need
not be present. When it is not present the behavior would be the same
as before. When it is present, the domains that are being created are
checked to see that it is not an effective TLD.

This change offers the designate administrator the ability to configure
2 lists to indicate the TLDs(accepted_tlds_file) and SLDs and others
that effectively act as TLDs.(effective_tlds_file)

2 sample files are included to show the format required for these files.
The TLD file is from http://data.iana.org/TLD/tlds-alpha-by-domain.txt
Commented lines in this file begin with a #. There is one entry per line
and the entries are in the IDNA format.

The sample effective TLD file is from http://publicsuffix.org/list/
This file is in the UTF-8 format. Lines beginning with a // and ! are
ignored. The wildcard character * (asterisk) may only be used to
wildcard the topmost level in a domain name. All the entries are
converted to idna format.

Change-Id: I3d2f7e2741f4cda0b227e4a5671b141f99052291
Closes-Bug: #1249396

commit_message:
Switch Ubuntu element to installing saucy.

In tests, saucy has been able to match raring for the ability to bring
up clouds, so we can roll forwards and switch the default to saucy.

Change-Id: I4df35d40f902c0daa7b2761d7afea8db25526753

commit_message:
Improve the UX around sample config generation

This commit just adds some documentation around using the sample config
generator. It also adds a wrapper script that sets the env variable for
running the oslo generator script with tempest.

Change-Id: I860b17defeeb85174e68b1e8b046b0e43c30683b

commit_message:
Remove the collector submodule

It's useless to have a submodule with just one service, simplify the
hierarchy.

Change-Id: I4c39ea74fc5cb59d487626b998eaed9c5cf30eff

Agreed with Tong. I think we should at least give the user an option to only start rpc or udp collector."}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-11-21 10:10:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

What's really the point of adding yet another configuration option vs having something that works in all cases by default?"}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-11-21 13:49:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Julien, the difference is that if the decision is made by the
deployer or it has been made for deployer. I may have missed
something here, but seems to me now if I start collector, I
start both vs. I can start one and leave the other not
running. That is what bothers me. If this is simply changing
the default setting, I am ok with, but I do not see how you
can configure it so that only one runs and the other does not.'}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-11-21 13:53:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

In the future, there might be more collector, let's say there
will be an email collector, will we also start that
altogether? I would say no.  One of the good things that I
like ceilometer about is how flexible it is in terms
enabling features. We can pretty much configure it the way
we want at many different levels. Combine these two seems to
me moving to a different direction."}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-11-21 14:08:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I think there's something here, but none of you have the good arguments. :)

commit_message:
Use all available headroom for autoscaling

Fixes bug 1254796

Previously, potential headroom for autoscaling group growth
or shrinkage would remain unused unless the adjustment exactly
hit the max or min size respectively.

Now, we truncate the adjustment to the upper or lower bound
in the case of an over-shoot.

Change-Id: I760be999039f7038dab77cb8b77a0f683ef56db3

commit_message:
Send only one agent notification on port update

This patch removes the other redundant notification sent in the same
routine to notify whether a security group changed.

Closes-Bug: #1254924
Partial Blueprint neutron-tempest-parallel

Change-Id: I5bad015decdc197c3fa9b58c680564380d513bc4

commit_message:
Implement PrivateIpAddress attribute

The PrivateIpAddress attribute maps to the private IP address of the
AWS::EC2::NetworkInterface resource.

Change-Id: I471e9ab9ea6fed8bc09a6339d11bcf1f1e4528f8
Closes-Bug: #1254675

commit_message:
Pass Instance object to get_spice_console virt api

Update the virt API to be defined as taking an Instance object.
Luckily, no real changes are needed in the virt drivers to make this
work.  While the API is changing anyway, pass the context in as well
since we have a TODO to add it to virt API methods when convenient.

Change-Id: I2b2f389aee3f2cee3bb1361958da797735c60e18

commit_message:
Add 'warning' as an alias to 'warn'

The standard Python logging system uses 'warning' and not 'warn'. To
ease compatibility with it, let's add 'warning' too.

Change-Id: I7778d7960ca7a72be007cb083e5434ede6e3fe6e

commit_message:
The param 'readonly' is incorrect checked

In the function os-update_readonly_flag, the param 'readonly' is incorrect
checked, without the param in request, i think it should raise exception
with message like "Must specify readonly in request."

Change-Id: I19e15e988ffa2d093d374f6a33ce94d45ffe2c30
Closes-bug: 1254682

commit_message:
Allow custom headers when using swift download (CLI)

This fixes bug #1051046

A repeatable option, --header or -H, is added so a user can specify
custom headers such as Range or If-Modified-Since when downloading
an object with the swift CLI.

Change-Id: I1f7dcf64cf625f2e5a4488c210894cfe6e0d5974

May be this will change the stance!"}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-11-11 19:47:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Nikhil,

Thanks for the prompt response.

I see, yeah I think it is up to each project. For example, nova, heat, oslo-incubator, oslo.config, and cinder have accepted similar changes, but neutron did not. 

In general I think it's a helpful change that makes it easier for those developers that use Eclipse, or other IDEs, and it doesn't really affect those that don't since the change is completely invisible to them.

commit_message:
Add eclipse project files to .gitignore

Like some of the other projects (nova, heat, oslo, cinder) git ignore
eclipse project files. This will remove manual steps for people
developing from eclipse.

Change-Id: Ib908c8d419072b440f5ec647bea8f13b97e48f7c

commit_message:
Make _notify a public method

Having it private isn't worth it if you already have a string containing
the priority that you want. Plus, its publisher_id argument in that case
is never used.

Change-Id: Ibd3fac15f52f662298cc8a4f86724c2bae133470

Skip test_arbitrary_attributes_* in _ldap_livetest

Live LDAP tests fail because the test
test_arbitrary_attributes_are_returned_from_create_user
doesn't work.

commit_message:
Add tftp_server pattern in ironic.conf

This is the fix for bug 1236623. Currently we used $my_ip as the
tftp_server, but we do need a dedicated config option especially
when the provisioning network and public network for nova are
different.

Change-Id: I4b619319cee55c974027a2c4667230a6a499628f
Partial-Bug: #1236623

commit_message:
Add David Chadwick as ATC

Professor David Chadwick has been deeply involved in keystone's
[painstakingly slow] shift towards a federated identity model for over a
year now. I think all of keystone-core can vouch for the value of his
technical contributions on the matter. He regularly participates on the
-dev mailing list and in gerrit:

  https://review.openstack.org/#/q/owner:6534+OR+reviewer:6534,n,z

Change-Id: Ia2557c17c43fb280c85122d75e513472a320cc4d

commit_message:
Call _destroy_metadata_proxy from _destroy_router_namespaces

Refactor _spawn/destroy_metadata_proxy so that it can be called
with only the namespace and the router_id.

Change-Id: Id1c33b22c7c3bd35c54a7c9ad419831bfed8746b
Closes-Bug: #1252856

commit_message:
Add FloatField for objects

This adds a Float field type for objects, which will be required for
things like Flavor.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects

Change-Id: I260a9855721046f3af24db102a24b974bfb3518a

commit_message:
Remove update_service_capabilities from scheduler rpc api

This method was already unused in the code base, so it can be
immediately removed from the client rpc api.  It must remain on the
server side (scheduler manager) until the api receives a major version
bump.

Related to blueprint rpc-major-version-updates-icehouse

Change-Id: I689bef71cc3db887bc571b9c364ee906a5a927f4

commit_message:
Sync log_handler module from Oslo

Ibf28ba17f Remove the notifier and its dependencies from log.py

Move the code related to the publish error handler out of the
log module so its easier for other projects to consume it

Closes-bug: #1240349

Generic Receive Offload appears to be enabled by default on recent Ubuntu
kernels. It can have a significant impact on download performance when
enabled on a Neutron router interface. This patch warns users about that.

Change-Id: I3d3a560b1db55aabd901f27ad5c7bd5777b300da
Closes-bug: 1252900
(cherry picked from commit 3cc8efdf5466750334e912ae8efa4cc8c0354edb)
'}]
commit_message:
Add warning about GRO and Neutron routers

Generic Receive Offload appears to be enabled by default on recent Ubuntu
kernels. It can have a significant impact on download performance when
enabled on a Neutron router interface. This patch warns users about that.

Change-Id: I3d3a560b1db55aabd901f27ad5c7bd5777b300da
Closes-bug: 1252900
(cherry picked from commit 3cc8efdf5466750334e912ae8efa4cc8c0354edb)

commit_message:
Remove deprecated auth_token middleware

The actual code for auth_token has been moved python-keystoneclient
since Grizzly, and keep it in keystone for backward compatibility
over Havana Release. So now we can safely remove it in Icehouse.

bp icehouse-deprecated-removed

Change-Id: I6bfc92c2cb9d836bdc7130910a679a8b660096e9

commit_message:
Add documentation for Read Only LDAP configuration option.

This patch adds a new section for describing the Read Only
LDAP configuration option that is now available in Havana.

Closes-Bug: #1235778

Change-Id: I964d410d247083a8ff43b0177cb0b2ba920310fd

commit_message:
Use common ratelimit middleware for v2 and v3

We have two copies for limit middleware those used for v2 and v3 api.
But there isn't any different between the two copies of code. So we
should remove duplicated code. This patch removes limits middleware
in v3 code and test, and adds new parameter for limits middleware that
used to point out which version's DEFUALT_LIMITS rules will be used.

Closes-bug: 1252596

Change-Id: I5d827517bf7ef5c6af4b227e594217f830a8c1fd

commit_message:
Enforce unique constraint on neutron pool members

Neutron loadbalancer pool members should not be allowed to have
duplicate address/port tuples in the same pool.

Change-Id: Ie52c6033217ec05ee4f59bcf8a0e4167c7b13663
Closes-Bug: #1251867

commit_message:
Clean up "target" interface to policy

The docstring is wrong for this argument, and we pass an empty
dict since we're not using this data for policy decisions at
the moment, so default it inside common.policy.Enforcer.

Change-Id: I298e691e12ed10825327492f02bd2f4edec24323

commit_message:
Handle '%' in Swift container names.

When a Swift container name contains '%', it breaks many URL
leading to "HTTP 400 Bad request" under Apache.
(Not reproducible with Django development server)

It is due to a Django bug in django.core.urlresolvers.reverse():
"urlresolvers.reverse() generates invalid URLs when an argument contains % character"
https://code.djangoproject.com/ticket/13260
This bug have been fixed in Django 1.6.

In the meanwhile, this patch handles '%' in URL thanks to
django.utils.http.urlquote()

Unit tests have been updated accordingly and
helper functions are now tested.

Change-Id: Ifbe781f66458df0bd013dc935f55ad0ac2c5ac61
Closes-Bug: #1231904

(1 inline comment)

I suggest simpler and cleaner way to form validator.py.

We can create a decorator(ish) method:

    def validated_type(f):
        class __inner(object):
            def __instancecheck__(self, instance):
                return f(instance)
        return __inner()

And then for complex check use:

    @validated_type
    def string_integer(instance):
        try:
            int(instance)
        except ValueError:
            return False
        else:
            return True

And for simple checks use:

    ipv6 = validated_type(utils.is_valid_ipv6)

This will lead to much cleaner and simpler code."}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2013-03-26 20:47:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (4 inline comments)

Hi Yuriy,

Thanks for your reviews.

> I guess, separate change request is OK for this case.

I see, thanks.

> What do you want to use instead of JSON Schema? Why?

JSON Schema library cannot judge undefined parameter is invalid, and I feel it is better that this framework can do it.
If the above validation is not implemented, it is a little difficult to keep complete API schema when adding new parameters. Because API method can be executed, even if forgetting to add a new parameter to API schema.
I don't have any other idea and I will investigate Quantum's validation and the other.

I created a etherpad page for better design. I'm glad if you write comments/ideas on it.
https://etherpad.openstack.org/NovaApiValidationFramework

> If you write at least some unittests early you'll see benefits while developing new checks and trying new approaches. So I advice to do it as soon as possible.

Thanks, I will add some unittests ASAP!"}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2013-03-29 02:11:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'd like to discuss whether this framework should be implemented for Havana or not.

On Oslo patch(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/25884/), we discussed which is better
validation mechanism WSME or jsonschema. Now we do not archive the consensus.

On the other hand, Nova v3 API will be implemented with current WSGI not WSME due to Havana schedule,
according to http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-May/008355.html.

Then, I think the discussion point for Nova is simple.
"For Nova v3 API, is this framework is necessary or not?"

I'm sorry for this festinating.
But now I need to make a decision (continue this task for Hahava or not) due to its schedule.
Any comments are welcome.'}, {'account_id': 5174, 'date': '2013-06-05 12:22:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

Hi Ken'ichi 

It seems a good thing to have IMHO since we're not going to use wsme now. Although I cannot talk by the other developers, so I suggest you to bring this up in the nova-meeting this week.

I don't know how wsme valadation works, but I imagine that this at least prepares stuff to be validated outside api code, which is good and will help if, in future, we replace jsonschema mechanism by wsme's."}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2013-06-05 13:44:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

Thanks for your advice.

To be honesty, I never mind even if implementing with WSME.
but I don't want to throw the code away again when the validation code with WSME is almost complete, because it would have been reviewed/helped by many people.
so I'd like to discuss this to achieve a concrete consensus."}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2013-06-06 01:51:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2013-06-24 02:31:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Looks fine - just a question about the way that the testing of fixed_ips validation is done in the unittests. I'm wondering is there an advantage to the way you have done it compared to say creating a wsgi_app_v3 object and then looking for what exception is raised? See the v3 test_keypairs unittests as an example. The wsgi_app_v3 approach doesn't require the interim fake response function, though it does sort of test from a higher level."}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2013-06-24 08:59:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

Thanks, Christopher

First of all, I am changing this patch because I've gotten an idea from the comments of Mauro and Yuuichi.

The idea is that moves API validation operation from WSGI to each API method by using decorator.
By moving it to API method, we can test the validation only by API method(e.g. result = self.controller.action (**params**)) and we will be able to move Pecan/WSME(or any framework) + jsonschema smoothly in the future because of reducing necessary WSGI code.

So unittests of v3 fixed_ips will not need WSGI.Resource and that will fit current unittests."}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2013-06-24 09:06:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

one more thing,

I have written the sample code of Pecan/WSME + jsonschema on the following:
https://etherpad.openstack.org/NovaApiValidationFramework

Of course, Pecan/WSME is out of scope for Nova v3 API and this sample is not useful now. but I'd like to share this for the future."}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2013-06-24 09:32:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 25.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-06-24 10:22:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 25: Works for me

Hi Joe,

because the API validation of this framework is executed with the decorator of API method, that means this framework does not depend on web framework.

For example, Pecan/WSME returns a error response if an exception happens at API method/decorator of API method.

To test the above idea, I wrote the sample code on https://etherpad.openstack.org/NovaApiValidationFramework.
Please see the section of "Sample code of Pecan/WSME + jsonschma" if you need.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2013-07-29 05:57:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 34:

Hi Joe,

Your ".. use this over Pecan/WSME" would mean "what are advantages of JSON Schema over Pecan/WSME?", right?
If so, I misunderstood your comment as "how to overlap this on Pecan/WSME" and I will add the following log in commit message.

The advantages of JSON Schema:
* Easy to implement strict API validation which checks parameter types, lengths, ranges and formats.
* JSON Schema is portable. It would be a bonus for them to be able to use those schemas both to validate their messages and serve as authoritative documentation of what messages the API will accept.

Also WSME/Pecan is out of scope for nova v3 api, we cannot use original validation of WSME/Pecan now.
Even if we implement API validation with JSON Schema, we will be able to continue to use JSON Schema by overlapping it when implementing nova v4 api with Pecan/WSME.

Summary of the discussion: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-July/011410.html'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-07-29 21:26:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 34:

commit_message:
Add API input validation framework

This patch adds a core part of API validation framework.
Other patches of each API schema are necessary.

The validation method is implemented with jsonschema library,
and some features are added:
 * validate minimum/maximum value of string number(ex. "10")
 * validate uuid string format

This framework can validate requests of both JSON and XML,
because of validating data after JSON/XML deserialization.

The API schema files for Nova v3 API will be created under
nova/api/openstack/compute/schemas/v3. For preparing these
files, this patch adds some __init__.py files.

blueprint nova-api-validation-fw

Change-Id: Ieba96718264ad2ddfba63b65425f7e5bbb8606a9

commit_message:
Pin iso8601 to >=0.1.4 for compatibility with Grizzly

Grizzly stable Glance requires iso8601<=0.1.4, so we need to add this
limit to pass jenkins tests.

Change-Id: I1b5089c6a953ebd36aef4917f65321fc059e2722
Closes-bug: 1255419

commit_message:
powervm: remove powervm virt driver from nova

IBM's strategic direction for OpenStack powervm support
is to support powervc, and therefore support is being
pulled out for the existing powervm IVM/VIOS driver.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I9b7887c1914def145e87cf20dbd0ec65cb0fe987

[{'created': '2013-11-19 15:27:55.000000000', 'message': '    Adds remote docker registry support

    The Docker container manager uses its own registry service to manage
    docker containers and docker repositories.  Initial implementation
    assumed that registry service was on the same node as the container.
    This commit allows the Nova administrator to indicate a single IP
    for the centralized Docker registry by adding the optional config
    variable: registry_default_ip to nova.conf.  This is an optional
    variable, and it defaults to 127.0.0.1, which satisfies the original
    authors intended use case.

    Closes-Bug: #1248387

Change-Id: I8592bde1617e9fd826a2b3c91cb315ed35d096f4
'}]
commit_message:
Adds remote docker registry support

    The Docker container manager uses its own registry service to manage
    docker containers and docker repositories.  Initial implementation
    assumed that registry service was on the same node as the container.
    This commit allows the Nova administrator to indicate a single IP
    for the centralized Docker registry by adding the optional config
    variable: registry_default_ip to nova.conf.  This is an optional
    variable, and it defaults to 127.0.0.1, which satisfies the original
    authors intended use case.

    Closes-Bug: #1248387

Change-Id: I8592bde1617e9fd826a2b3c91cb315ed35d096f4

commit_message:
Taskflow persistence

Store task flow persistence in DB, this allow creation of API (in
progress) that will provide execution information like progress.

This patch now in progress, it's early version for community review.

Implemments blueprint: backend-activity

Change-Id: Ie1c80c44f01eb8e19c14d5f638ce4167fc7f416b

commit_message:
Update glance/openstack/common from oslo Part 2

Update from oslo:
- glance/openstack/common/crypto/
- glance/openstack/common/rpc/
- glance/openstack/common/sslutils.py

And update openstack-common.conf

Oslo commit: 764ad35e89d20008bf48d17e4129cfce5b717a6c

Change-Id: I98ab6708c812be1f0b3e52b3d7df660172384d0c

normalized before storage, and that when reading the attribute from a
given file that it matches its name (since it was stored that way).

commit_message:
Verify X-Timestamp matches on-disk file name

Verify that the metadata X-Timestamp value is properly normalized
before storage in the file using that timestamp in its name, and that
the retrieved timestamp attribute matches the name of the file from
which it is read.

Change-Id: I66c49d69ad2906a73a92b8533411f303ccf9bbf5
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

So this change is a *proposal* that I am backing that came out of discussions with @clayg.

In summary, it appears the auditor benefits from just using internal knowledge of how things should be to audit what the REST API layer is doing, and leaves the DiskFile class to be just about the backend interface for the object server REST API layer, leaving a backend implementation free to manage its internals separately from the object server code requirements.

Background:

We noticed that the operation of the auditor starts by using audit_location_generator which already knows the intimate details of the on-disk layout of a drive used by the current implementation (this is perfectly reasonable).

The auditor then reads the metadata directly for an object and then invokes the DiskFile interface using the a,c,o triple calculated from the stored name.

It then uses the DiskFile class to reference a potentially different file (not guaranteed to be the .data file that was given by audit_location_generator because, IIRC, nothing is checking to see if DiskFile comes up with the same underlying path) and audits that file by using the DiskFile class to ensure the content-length metadata value matches the file system size (.get_data_file_size()) and that the *optionally* stored ETag matches the calculated MD5 hash resulting from reading the entire file. This is optional in that, currently, if the object does not have an ETag it will read the entire file and then not doing anything, hence commit https://review.openstack.org/44995.

So recognizing that the auditor already has so much internal knowledge, and we are trying to drive the DiskFile API primarily for the REST API of the object server, and that we seem to gain a bit of efficiency by reading directly, it seemed worth to pull the DiskFile use out of the auditor.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-09-04 23:26:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: No score

(1 inline comment)

I *think* this is a good idea?  in principle?  maybe?

There's an unhandled exception when you get multiple .data files in a directory (like while a replication is in progress):

http://paste.openstack.org/show/46595/

If we got this route, I think it's important to move more of diskfile's logical methods (i.e. get_ondisk_file) out into module functions (e.g. get_data_file_size).  The iter/drop_cache/etag check is a bit trickier.

In the long run I think decoupling may make it easier to implement more advanced checks, like bulkstat, and the name_hash check - that name_hash check is a killer feature I think, I say go ahead and sneak a fakey get_part in there and *really* see what's up!)

I did some instrumentation on os, os.path, getsize, whatever I could think of - this patch seems to do pretty much the same stuff as the orig (I'm actually seeing one less stat call because the old auditor would call get_data_file_size manually, but then hit it again on the first close when trying to get at the etag auto quarantine - so WIN!)

Random: I think the logging messages could be a touch more consistent with wording, and maybe even fixed up so they only mention the object's full path once:

http://paste.openstack.org/show/46598/

I didn't look at the tests to hard, but there was that one think on the builtins mock inline.

I wonder if we could get redbo to look at this change seeing as how he keeps pretending he's going to do that bulkstat stuff - maybe this makes that easier/harder/nochange?"}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-09-11 19:27:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-10-11 18:56:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

Alright, so I've been staring at this for a bit, and I think I figured out what seems weird to me.

Mainly, it's odd that you're calling diskfile.get_ondisk_file(datadir), which requires a listdir, right after the audit_location_generator just listed that directory.

I think what would make this go down a little easier is if audit_location_generator were to only yield things that really should be audited; then we can skip all the checking. If we swapped out the suffix param for a callable that took a hash-directory listing* and handed back file-to-audit/None (and then audit_location_generator filters out the Nones), then we could avoid that second listdir entirely.

* the thing under the suffix dir: /srv/node/$device/$part/$suffix/$hash/$timestamp.suffix"}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-10-11 19:14:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

That sounds like a good idea, I'll spin that and see how that comes out."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-10-12 00:53:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

I was thinking about some stuff, in particular the use of hash_cleanup_listdir in the auditor to get the right filenames out.

I came up with this half-baked diff: http://paste.openstack.org/show/yUMNTpI2jFY727SS8eHr/

I wrote a function in there that takes a directory listing and turns it into datafile, metafile, tombstone, and stale, unlinkable files. I think it works.

The problem with just plugging in hash_cleanup_listdir in the auditor is that it modifies the filesystem by cleaning up stale things, and the auditor doesn't know reclaim_age because it's in a different part of the config file (or possibly a whole different config file). My thought with writing figure_out_hash_listdir() was to get the same logic as hash_cleanup_listdir() with respect to what's current vs. stale, but take out the bits that modify the filesystem so that it could be called from the auditor.

I hope that I'll get a little more time to work on this over the weekend, but in case I don't, here's a half-baked diff that might have the general idea in it.

Note that hash_cleanup_listdir() could almost certainly be refactored to use this function; I just didn't have time to do it yet."}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-10-18 06:07:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 14.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-18 06:55:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Works for me

(1 inline comment)

If you replace a *.data file with a similarly-named directory (like XFS might do), you get this message:

  ERROR Object /srv/node/d3/objects/670/4d0/a7b1e0125eaa035dd656699eb05fe4d0/1381994088.49548.data failed audit and will be quarantined: Error when reading metadata:

That's mostly good except for the bit at the end where the IOError(EISDIR) is not getting stringified (at diskfile.py line 382 or so).  For a bit, I was looking at the read_metadata instance method instead of the utility function.  But I guess it's the utility function which will be trying to call read_metadata on a directory... which I guess fails with some kind of exception which doesn't have a stringification?  Furthermore, read_metadata says it wants a filedescriptor, but isn't get_data_file() passing in a file path (string)?"}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-10-18 16:00:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14: (1 inline comment)

When I replace a .data file with a directory the exception that is raised is EOFError, which indicates there are no extended attributes on the directory (because I did not create any on it).  Is that what you see?

I'll post a patch which catches that error.

I tested that the error is getting stringified, but an EOFError does not have any string message on it (at least as raised by the xattr module).

As for the read_metadata and for that matter, write_metadata methods taking a file descriptor as their first parameter, the underlying xattr module functions used actually inspect that parameter and adapt to a string path, file pointer or file descriptor.  While we document it that way currently, we do use it in other places using a string (or at least in the past)."}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-10-18 18:03:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 15.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-18 18:38:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: Works for me

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-03 03:54:59.000000000', 'message': 'Ween the object auditor off of the DiskFile class

Given we are going in the direction that the DiskFile class is the
abstraction layer for the needs of the REST API layer, it seems that
the auditor should not use the same methods in order to truly
"audit". Instead, only the low-level on-disk file logic for the data
directory is shared, and all other verifications are performed using
direct inspections of the data.

As a result, the auditor performs a few more double checks to make
sure the "name" metadata attribute results in the same object data
file; adds some explicit error checking for quarantinable errors (bad
metadata, name does not hash back to the same data directory, unable
to open the file, unable to fstat the file). However, while the
current code will read the entire file only to find out that it does
not have a stored ETag, this code will skip the reading.

Possible related work:

  * Check that the X-Timestamp metadata value matches the given name
    of the object data file

Change-Id: I224e42d06ac49495a59e965502bcf3f323db1929
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>
