Thanks for the clarification - I'll review those related changes as well."}, {'account_id': 7461, 'date': '2013-07-18 12:52:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Firstly - I do like where you are going with this.

However, I would like to see a change made to the consume_from_instance method, so that scheduling decisions can be reflected in the HostState. Otherwise scheduling a set of instances would all come out with the same scheduling decision.

I realise that in the generic case it is not known what the nature of resource consumption would be (if any). So some way to indicate what the change should be would be needed. As decisions come from the filter/weight plugins, maybe that could be used as a model for a consumption function.

Without this change, this new way of handling resources is not more generic because it is not capable of doing what the existing one does for cpu, memory and disk. Ideally it would be possible not to handle these as a special case.

I am going to make a similar comment on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/35767/ which I think is the counterpart in compute.

But good work so far!"}, {'account_id': 4491, 'date': '2013-07-19 10:10:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 4491, 'date': '2013-07-19 10:23:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@Paul,

I think there are 2 types of resources. The first type is something like cpu utilization, network utilization, it is impossible to know how much of those resources will be consumed before launching the actual VM instance. The other type is something like the current vcpus, free_mem, of which we know how much to consume before launching the VM. The consume_from_instance() method can only apply to those resources of the 2nd type.

I agree that we need "some way to indicate what the change should be would be needed" for the 2nd type of resources. I'm thinking of adding those information into instance_extra_specs, the the key='resource_consume:<resource_name>', value=<value to consume>. Any comment?

Besides, how about we put these 'consume generic resources' changes made to both scheduler/nova-compute into another patch which depends on this one?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-19 11:09:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Works for me

'}, {'account_id': 7461, 'date': '2013-07-25 13:54:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I think this is changing more than it needs to, in particular I think you can leave the existing vcpu, disk and memory attributes as they are. The change does not improve their handling. If you want to access them all in a uniform way you can hide the difference in the accessor methods. Trying to handle them the same here is also inconsistent with https://review.openstack.org/#/c/35759/ and https://review.openstack.org/#/c/35767/ which don't.

In an earlier review you made the comment that there are two types of value: statically allocated resources and dynamic metrics based on-going utilization statistics. You also suggested that dealing with consume_from_compute_node (and the claims test at the compute node) can be worked out as a separate change. I agree with you on that. 

The code in this change handles the dynamic metrics type well. The existing vcpu, memory and disk values are all the statically allocated type and so subject to further change and may not fit your data structures. So I would leave them alone for now. 

Lastly, I'm not sure you need to override the __getattr__ and __setattr__ methods, it can get in the way. Why not use something like get_resource(name) and set_resource(name, resource)?"}, {'account_id': 7461, 'date': '2013-07-25 14:21:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

[{'created': '2013-07-05 08:48:59.000000000', 'message': 'Modify the HostState to be more generic.

Changes the HostState to be more generic and extensible to store other

commit_message:
Extend the scheduler HostState for metrics from compute_node

Changes the HostState to be more generic and extensible to store other
metrics from compute node for scheduling purpose.

This is part of the blueprint utilization-aware-scheduling.

Change-Id: Ia472e9dcdaf12371ffad94e074cecd51886a1c04

commit_message:
Replace 0 with untagged in verification message

Fix for representation on ui verification
with untagged interfaces
Currently across components 0 is used
as flag for untagged interface
I think that it is best to change
only representation for this flag on ui

Implements: https://mirantis.jira.com/browse/PRD-2450?filter=-1
Change-Id: Iaac4215a92f12b1316334ed44f6ef6cbf6b6892a

The issue I have with this is that this is so special-cased. We are crashing the service before it is loaded based on what seems to be internal implementation details of the compute service (for example how urls are generated).

I am thinking that this should be implemented as a hook on the manager class that gets called during the service start() method, but this seems to require us to change how managers and services interact which may require getting code accepted into oslo incubator first - so I am willing to let it slide, but let it be known that I thought it was ugly."}, {'account_id': 8910, 'date': '2013-10-30 13:38:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: (3 inline comments)

https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/compute/manager.py#L3593
and html5proxy_base_url:
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/compute/manager.py#L3628

I agree it's an ugly solution but that was as far as I could go for now. I'll see what would be the best place to put this code into.

commit_message:
Break nova on startup with misconfigured vnc urls

After configuring novnc with ssl/tls with a self-signed cert/key with
openssl horizon still provides the http vnc url. There are two settings
in the config file (nova.conf) "novncproxy_base_url" and
"html5proxy_base_url" that contain the full urls of the vnc proxy and
if they are not changed manually to https, then horizon displays a
server not found error. If it is manually updated to https then it
works as expected.
Because nova is responsible for the vnc urls, it shouldn't be started
when they are improperly configured. The person who is deploying nova is
disabled from starting the service until the proper values are set.

Closes-Bug: #1243614
Change-Id: I53480fe1c6b0c27a51daf451200c5a25923bfdd2

commit_message:
Don't return query from db API

The cell_update() method of the sqlalchemy db API returned a Query when
it really intended to return a Cell.  Fix this and tweak the db API test
so that it verifies that the result of this method is a Cell.

Closes-bug: #1198796

commit_message:
Fix _create_ephemeral to accept max_size kwarg.

Patch f6810be4ae1a6c93e7d8017ee67d5344dfdf4a30 introduced a max_size
kwarg into its calls to prepare_template. In the case where ephemeral
backing image files do not exist, these will turn into calls to
_create_ephemeral in the libvirt driver.

That needs to accept a max_size kwarg, even if it doesn't utilise it.

Fixes-Bug: #1250032
Change-Id: Iadc7359803f4462309e1d952e03b935766b6b598

commit_message:
Generic LXC share driver

Implements LXC share driver, that allows to isolate
share exporting beetwen different tenants by using
Linux Containers for each tenant.

Change-Id: Id7b8596c3f5b2e057d6f77cd6857637f514f1c09
